          "rules": [
            {
              "id": "022b63ea-ee16-3637-8691-8d5aae764e38",
              "name": "Cookie Lacks Secure, HttpOnly, And SameSite Flags",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nInsecure session cookie attributes. In Python web applications, a cookie that carries session or authentication state should explicitly enable Secure, HttpOnly, and SameSite protections. Without these flags, the browser may send the cookie over unencrypted HTTP, expose it to client-side script, or include it in cross-site requests that increase CSRF risk.\n\nThe sink shown sets a session-style cookie with encrypted user data but does not visibly set any protective attributes. Encryption of the cookie value does not replace browser-enforced cookie security controls. For a session cookie such as vulpy_session, set secure=True so it is only sent over HTTPS, httponly=True so JavaScript cannot read it, and samesite='Lax' or 'Strict' unless a cross-site flow is required.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nApply Secure, HttpOnly, and SameSite explicitly to every authentication, session, and other sensitive cookie at the point it is created. Use HTTPS everywhere so Secure cookies are always transmitted correctly. Prefer SameSite='Lax' for typical session cookies and use 'Strict' for more restrictive flows; only use 'None' when cross-site use is required, and combine it with Secure. Also define appropriate cookie scope with a narrow path, avoid unnecessary domain widening, and set Max-Age or Expires deliberately based on session requirements.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nresponse.set_cookie(\n    'vulpy_session',\n    fernet.encrypt((username + '|' + country).encode()).decode('utf-8'),\n    secure=True,\n    httponly=True,\n    samesite='Lax'\n)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nflask\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Secure Cookie Attribute](https://owasp.org/www-community/controls/SecureCookieAttribute)\n- [OWASP HttpOnly](https://owasp.org/www-community/HttpOnly)\n- [OWASP SameSite](https://owasp.org/www-community/SameSite)\n- [OWASP Session Management Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Session_Management_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-614: Sensitive Cookie in HTTPS Session Without 'Secure' Attribute](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/614.html)\n- [Flask Response.set_cookie API](https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/api/#flask.Response.set_cookie)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-614",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/614.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-614"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "04729de2-abc2-390f-b012-c5478da8adbb",
              "name": "Missing CSRF Protection In State-Changing Route",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-site request forgery protection is missing on a state-changing POST route. In this Flask handler, a logged-in user's browser can be induced to submit a POST request to the MFA enable endpoint because the route reads form data and changes account state without visible CSRF token enforcement.\n\nFor Python Flask applications, session cookies are sent automatically by the browser, so checking only that the user is logged in does not prove the request originated from your own form. This endpoint enables MFA after validating an OTP, which is still a sensitive state change and should require a per-request CSRF token, with optional Origin or Referer validation as an additional defense.\n\nApply CSRF protection at the framework layer so every unsafe method is covered consistently, and ensure the HTML form that posts otp includes the generated token. If a global solution is not yet available, add a route-level token check and reject requests with missing or invalid tokens before processing the form.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nEnable CSRF protection globally for the Flask application so all state-changing POST, PUT, PATCH, and DELETE routes are covered by default. Use a standard Flask CSRF implementation that binds a server-generated token to the user session and require the token on every HTML form that changes application state.\n\nFor this MFA enable flow, render the token in the form and validate it before reading otp or updating MFA state. Keep the route limited to authenticated users, and add Origin or Referer checks for browser-based form submissions as a secondary control, not a replacement for CSRF tokens. Also ensure session cookies are configured with Secure, HttpOnly, and an appropriate SameSite value to reduce cross-site request risk.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom flask import Blueprint, flash, g, redirect, render_template, request\nfrom flask_wtf import FlaskForm, CSRFProtect\nfrom wtforms import StringField, SubmitField\nfrom wtforms.validators import DataRequired\nimport pyotp\n\ncsrf = CSRFProtect()\nmod_mfa = Blueprint('mod_mfa', __name__)\n\n\nclass MFAEnableForm(FlaskForm):\n    otp = StringField('One-time password', validators=[DataRequired()])\n    submit = SubmitField('Enable MFA')\n\n\n@mod_mfa.route('/', methods=['GET', 'POST'])\ndef do_mfa_enable():\n    if 'username' not in g.session:\n        return redirect('/user/login')\n\n    form = MFAEnableForm()\n\n    if request.method == 'POST':\n        if not form.validate_on_submit():\n            flash('Invalid or missing CSRF token')\n            return redirect('/mfa/')\n\n        secret = libmfa.mfa_get_secret(g.session['username'])\n        totp = pyotp.TOTP(secret)\n\n        if totp.verify(form.otp.data):\n            libmfa.mfa_enable(g.session['username'])\n            return redirect('/mfa/')\n\n        flash('The OTP was incorrect')\n        return redirect('/mfa/')\n\n    return render_template('mfa.enable.html', form=form)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nFlask-WTF\nWTForms\npyotp\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/csrf)\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Request Forgery Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross-Site_Request_Forgery_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-352: Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html)\n- [Flask-WTF CSRF Protection](https://flask-wtf.readthedocs.io/en/1.2.x/csrf/)\n- [Werkzeug Request Referer and Origin Handling](https://werkzeug.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/wrappers/#werkzeug.wrappers.request.Request.referrer)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-352",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-352"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "05a50fe8-ea34-3d2d-843f-c88f9dddaf30",
              "name": "Cookie Lacks Secure, HttpOnly, And SameSite Flags",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThis is an insecure session cookie configuration issue. A session or authentication cookie is being created without explicitly enabling the cookie attributes that protect it during transport, browser access, and cross-site requests.\n\nIn Python web applications, calling set_cookie without Secure, HttpOnly, and SameSite can leave a session token exposed to theft or misuse. Without Secure, the cookie can be sent over unencrypted HTTP. Without HttpOnly, client-side JavaScript can read it if an injection bug exists. Without SameSite, the browser is more likely to include the cookie in cross-site requests, increasing CSRF risk.\n\nFor the shown sink, the session cookie should be set with all three attributes explicitly. Use secure=True, httponly=True, and samesite set to an appropriate policy such as 'Lax' or 'Strict'. Authentication and session cookies should also avoid unnecessary scope and should have a bounded lifetime where appropriate.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nSet Secure, HttpOnly, and SameSite explicitly on every authentication or session cookie instead of relying on framework defaults. Use Secure for any cookie that must never travel over plain HTTP, HttpOnly to prevent access from browser scripts, and SameSite='Lax' or 'Strict' unless a documented cross-site flow requires 'None'. If SameSite=None is required, also keep Secure enabled.\n\nLimit cookie exposure further by setting the narrowest practical path and domain, using a short expiration or max_age for session-related values, and rotating session identifiers after authentication or privilege changes. Prefer storing only an opaque session identifier in the cookie rather than sensitive user data.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nresponse.set_cookie(\n    'vulpy_session',\n    session,\n    secure=True,\n    httponly=True,\n    samesite='Lax'\n)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nfrom http import cookies\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Secure Cookie Attribute](https://owasp.org/www-community/controls/SecureCookieAttribute)\n- [OWASP HttpOnly](https://owasp.org/www-community/HttpOnly)\n- [MDN Set-Cookie header](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Headers/Set-Cookie)\n- [CWE-614: Sensitive Cookie in HTTPS Session Without 'Secure' Attribute](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/614.html)\n- [CWE-1004: Sensitive Cookie Without 'HttpOnly' Flag](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/1004.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-614",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/614.html"
                  },
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-1004",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/1004.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-614",
                  "CWE-1004"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "0c3e64a2-bf70-38b3-83ff-7367097fc8d1",
              "name": "Weak Or Broken Hash Function Used",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nWeak cryptographic hash usage. This code computes a digest with hashlib.new(ALGORITHM, key).hexdigest(), which is unsafe when ALGORITHM can resolve to MD5 or SHA-1 for any security-sensitive purpose such as integrity checks, token derivation, signatures, or password-related handling.\n\nIn Python, selecting a hash algorithm dynamically makes it easy for weak primitives to remain enabled or be introduced later. Replace weak hashes with a strong fixed algorithm such as SHA-256 or SHA-512 for general hashing. If the value is used to protect authenticity, use HMAC with SHA-256 instead of a bare hash. If the value is derived from a password, use a password-based KDF such as hashlib.pbkdf2_hmac, bcrypt, scrypt, or Argon2 rather than a single fast hash.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not allow MD5 or SHA-1 for security decisions. Remove algorithm agility unless there is a strict compatibility requirement, and pin the implementation to SHA-256 or stronger. Use bare hashes only for non-adversarial fingerprinting. For message authenticity or signed values, use HMAC with a strong digest. For passwords, use a dedicated password hashing function with a unique salt and a work factor appropriate for your environment. Also ensure the input is handled as bytes consistently to avoid accidental encoding differences across platforms.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nimport hashlib\nimport hmac\nimport secrets\n\n# For non-password security-sensitive hashing, pin a strong algorithm.\nlastkey = hashlib.sha256(key).hexdigest()\n\n# If authenticity is required, prefer HMAC over a bare hash.\nsecret = secrets.token_bytes(32)\nlastkey = hmac.new(secret, key, hashlib.sha256).hexdigest()\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nhashlib\nhmac\nsecrets\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Cryptographic Storage Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cryptographic_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [OWASP Password Storage Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Password_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-328: Use of Weak Hash](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/328.html)\n- [Python hashlib documentation](https://docs.python.org/3/library/hashlib.html)\n- [Python hmac documentation](https://docs.python.org/3/library/hmac.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-328",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/328.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-328"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "11fb13bd-f21c-3834-95e5-4098a20edc6a",
              "name": "Missing CSRF Protection In State-Changing Route",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-site request forgery in a state-changing Flask route. This handler accepts a POST request that changes the authenticated user's password, but it does not show any CSRF token validation before reading form fields and performing the update.\n\nIn Flask applications, a password-change endpoint must verify that the POST originated from the application's own form and not from a malicious site using the victim's active session. Without CSRF protection, an attacker can cause a logged-in user to submit an unwanted password change request from another origin.\n\nProtect this route by enabling framework-level CSRF validation for form submissions and including a CSRF token in the rendered form. For sensitive state-changing actions like password updates, also restrict the route to POST only and optionally enforce same-origin checks using the Origin or Referer header as a defense in depth measure.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nEnable CSRF protection globally in the Flask application with Flask-WTF or equivalent middleware so every unsafe form POST is validated automatically. Render a per-request CSRF token in the password change form and reject requests with missing or invalid tokens before processing input.\n\nKeep password changes on POST-only endpoints and avoid performing state changes on GET. For high-impact actions such as credential updates, add same-origin validation using the Origin header, with Referer checking only as a fallback when needed. Ensure the session cookie is configured with Secure, HttpOnly, and an appropriate SameSite value to reduce cross-site request risk further.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom flask import abort, flash, render_template, request, session\nfrom flask_wtf import FlaskForm, CSRFProtect\nfrom wtforms import PasswordField, SubmitField\nfrom wtforms.validators import DataRequired, EqualTo, ValidationError\n\ncsrf = CSRFProtect()\n\n\ndef init_app(app):\n    app.config['SECRET_KEY'] = app.config.get('SECRET_KEY')\n    csrf.init_app(app)\n\n\nclass ChangePasswordForm(FlaskForm):\n    password = PasswordField('Password', validators=[DataRequired()])\n    password_again = PasswordField(\n        'Confirm password',\n        validators=[DataRequired(), EqualTo('password', message=\"The passwords don't match\")]\n    )\n    submit = SubmitField('Change password')\n\n    def validate_password(self, field):\n        if not libuser.password_complexity(field.data):\n            raise ValidationError(\"The password doesn't comply with complexity requirements\")\n\n\n@mod_user.route('/chpasswd', methods=['POST'])\ndef do_chpasswd():\n    origin = request.headers.get('Origin')\n    if origin and origin != request.host_url.rstrip('/'):\n        abort(403)\n\n    form = ChangePasswordForm()\n    if not form.validate_on_submit():\n        return render_template('user.chpasswd.html', form=form), 400\n\n    libuser.password_change(session['username'], form.password.data)\n    flash('Password changed')\n    return render_template('user.chpasswd.html', form=form)\n\n\n@mod_user.route('/chpasswd', methods=['GET'])\ndef chpasswd_form():\n    form = ChangePasswordForm()\n    return render_template('user.chpasswd.html', form=form)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nFlask-WTF\nWTForms\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/csrf)\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Request Forgery Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross-Site_Request_Forgery_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-352: Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html)\n- [Flask-WTF CSRF Protection](https://flask-wtf.readthedocs.io/en/1.2.x/csrf/)\n- [Flask Patterns for Forms](https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/patterns/wtforms/)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-352",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-352"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "12cd3453-2894-30ee-9d1d-c4b4fa8207fe",
              "name": "Insecure HTTP Request",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nInsecure transport of sensitive data. This Python code sends credentials with requests.post() over http://, which transmits the username and password without TLS protection.\n\nBecause the request targets an unencrypted endpoint, anyone with network visibility can intercept or modify the traffic. Even on internal networks or loopback-style development patterns, application code should use HTTPS for authenticated API calls so the same code path remains safe when deployed and so certificate validation can protect the connection.\n\nReplace the URL with an https:// endpoint and keep TLS certificate verification enabled. If this service is local or internal, configure it with a valid TLS certificate or a trusted internal CA rather than falling back to plaintext HTTP or disabling verification.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nUse HTTPS for all requests that carry credentials, session tokens, API keys, or other sensitive data. Do not disable certificate verification in requests, and avoid verify=False except in tightly controlled test code that never ships. For internal services, issue certificates from a trusted internal CA or terminate TLS at a trusted reverse proxy. Also set reasonable timeouts and handle TLS errors explicitly so insecure fallbacks are not introduced during error handling.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nimport requests\n\npayload = {\n    \"username\": username,\n    \"password\": password,\n}\n\nr = requests.post(\n    \"https://127.0.1.1:5000/api/key\",\n    json=payload,\n    timeout=10,\n)\nr.raise_for_status()\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nrequests\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Insecure Transport](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Insecure_Transport)\n- [CWE-319: Cleartext Transmission of Sensitive Information](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/319.html)\n- [Requests: SSL Cert Verification](https://requests.readthedocs.io/en/latest/user/advanced/#ssl-cert-verification)\n- [OWASP Transport Layer Security Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Transport_Layer_Security_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-319",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/319.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "3.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-319"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "14bbcf82-8d6c-3281-8852-b4c567abfced",
              "name": "Weak Or Broken Hash Function Used",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nInsecure hash algorithm usage. This code computes a digest through hashlib.new(ALGORITHM, ...), which allows weak algorithms such as MD5 or SHA-1 to be selected at runtime. In Python, those algorithms remain available for compatibility, but they are not appropriate for security-sensitive uses because collision attacks are practical or substantially weakened.\n\nFor integrity checks, signatures, tokens, or other security decisions, use a modern hash such as SHA-256 or SHA-512 and avoid algorithm names coming from configuration or user-controlled input unless they are strictly allowlisted. If this value is used for password storage or password verification, a general-purpose hash is also the wrong primitive; use a password-based key derivation function instead, such as PBKDF2-HMAC with a unique random salt and a high iteration count.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nReplace dynamic hash selection with an explicit strong algorithm such as hashlib.sha256() when the value is used for integrity or security decisions. If the application must support configurable algorithms, enforce a strict allowlist that excludes MD5 and SHA-1. For password handling, do not use hexdigest() of any general-purpose hash; use hashlib.pbkdf2_hmac() with a per-password random salt, sufficient iterations, and secure comparison during verification. Review nearby code to determine whether the digest is used for passwords, signatures, cache keys, or non-security purposes, and choose the primitive accordingly.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nimport hashlib\n\nresult = hashlib.sha256(response.encode(\"utf-8\")).hexdigest()\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nhashlib (Python standard library)\nos (Python standard library)\nhmac (Python standard library)\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Password Storage Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Password_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [OWASP Cryptographic Storage Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cryptographic_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-327: Use of a Broken or Risky Cryptographic Algorithm](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/327.html)\n- [Python hashlib documentation](https://docs.python.org/3/library/hashlib.html)\n- [Python pbkdf2_hmac documentation](https://docs.python.org/3/library/hashlib.html#hashlib.pbkdf2_hmac)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-327",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/327.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-327"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "152024d8-de8a-3c1a-a12f-6f3885fe83da",
              "name": "Hardcoded Configuration Detected",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nHardcoded secret in application configuration. In Python, embedding a Flask SECRET_KEY directly in source code exposes sensitive material to anyone who can read the repository, logs, build artifacts, or deployed files. If the key is disclosed, attackers can forge signed session data and weaken the trust boundary of the application.\n\nFor the sink shown here, assigning a literal value to app.config['SECRET_KEY'] should be replaced with loading the secret from the environment or a protected configuration source at runtime. This keeps the key out of version control, allows rotation without code changes, and supports different secrets per environment.\n\nThe application should also fail closed when the secret is missing instead of silently using an insecure default. Use a strong random value generated outside the codebase, store it in deployment secrets management, and rotate it according to operational policy.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nRemove hardcoded secrets from Python source files and load them at runtime from environment variables, a secrets manager, or protected configuration files that are excluded from version control. For Flask, set SECRET_KEY from deployment configuration and ensure production environments provide a strong unpredictable value.\n\nDo not replace the literal with another constant, test value, or fallback embedded in code. Validate that the variable is present during startup, restrict access to the secret in CI/CD and hosting platforms, and rotate the key if it has ever been committed or exposed.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nimport os\n\nsecret_key = os.environ[\"SECRET_KEY\"]\napp.config[\"SECRET_KEY\"] = secret_key\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nos\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Use of Hard-coded Password](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Use_of_hard-coded_password)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)\n- [Flask Configuration Handling](https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/config/#configuration-basics)\n- [Python os.environ documentation](https://docs.python.org/3/library/os.html#os.environ)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-798"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "1b24daf2-bb73-3e6f-b304-834a1ac59af6",
              "name": "Insecure Usage Of Temp File Or Directory",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nInsecure temporary file handling. Writing directly to a predictable path under /tmp in Python can allow other local users or processes to interfere with the file through pre-creation, symlink attacks, replacement, or unintended reads if permissions are too broad.\n\nIn this case, opening /tmp/ca.pub with open(..., 'wb') does not guarantee exclusive creation or safe ownership of the target file. If the path already exists or has been replaced with a symbolic link, the code may overwrite an attacker-controlled destination or disclose sensitive output. Use Python's tempfile facilities or create the file with exclusive creation and restrictive permissions so the filename is not guessable and the file cannot be hijacked.\n\nIf the file must persist, create it securely with a trusted API, set permissions to owner-only, write the content, and then atomically replace the final destination if needed. If persistence is not required, prefer a NamedTemporaryFile or TemporaryDirectory managed by the standard library.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nAvoid hard-coded, predictable filenames in shared temporary directories. Use the Python standard library tempfile module to create unique files securely, or open files with exclusive creation semantics using mode \"xb\" when a fixed name is unavoidable. Restrict permissions to the current user with 0o600 for files, and avoid following attacker-controlled paths.\n\nWhen a stable output filename is required, write to a securely created temporary file first and then atomically move it into place with os.replace. Prefer an application-specific directory with controlled ownership over /tmp when possible, and validate that the process does not operate on symlinks or pre-existing files created by other users.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nimport os\nimport tempfile\n\nwith tempfile.NamedTemporaryFile(mode=\"wb\", delete=False, dir=\"/tmp\") as out:\n    os.chmod(out.name, 0o600)\n    out.write(public_key_bytes)\n    temp_path = out.name\n\nfinal_path = \"/tmp/ca.pub\"\nos.replace(temp_path, final_path)\nos.chmod(final_path, 0o600)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nimport os\nimport tempfile\n\nPython standard library only; no external packages required.\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-377: Insecure Temporary File](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html)\n- [Python tempfile — Generate temporary files and directories securely](https://docs.python.org/3/library/tempfile.html)\n- [OWASP: Insecure Temporary File](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Insecure_Temporary_File)\n- [CWE-379: Creation of Temporary File in Directory with Insecure Permissions](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/379.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-377",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html"
                  },
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-379",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/379.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-377",
                  "CWE-379"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "1b5f7e3d-e6d9-3352-8bec-5afff4e82c69",
              "name": "Insecure HTTP Request",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nInsecure transport of sensitive data. This Python code sends credentials with requests.post over an http:// endpoint, which exposes the username and password to interception or modification by anyone able to observe network traffic between the client and server.\n\nWhen requests is used with HTTP, the request body is transmitted without TLS protection. For a login-style POST like this one, an attacker can capture credentials, tamper with the response, or redirect the request. Update the URL to use https://, keep certificate verification enabled, and fail closed if a secure endpoint is not available.\n\nIf the destination is configurable, validate that only HTTPS URLs are accepted before making the request. This prevents accidental downgrade to cleartext transport and ensures authentication data is only sent over encrypted connections.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nUse HTTPS for all requests that carry credentials, session tokens, personal data, or other sensitive content. Do not disable TLS certificate validation in requests, and do not suppress related warnings. Prefer hardcoded or centrally managed HTTPS endpoints, and validate configuration so non-HTTPS URLs are rejected before the request is sent.\n\nIf the remote service still exposes only HTTP, treat that as an insecure integration and upgrade the service or place it behind a properly configured TLS endpoint. Also consider using connect and read timeouts, certificate pinning or custom trust stores where appropriate, and avoiding redirects from HTTPS to HTTP.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom urllib.parse import urlparse\nimport requests\n\nparsed = urlparse(URL)\nif parsed.scheme.lower() != \"https\":\n    raise ValueError(\"Refusing to send credentials over a non-HTTPS connection\")\n\nresponse = requests.post(\n    URL,\n    data={\"username\": username, \"password\": password},\n    timeout=10,\n    verify=True,\n)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nrequests\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Transport Layer Protection Cheat Sheet](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Transport_Layer_Protection_Cheat_Sheet)\n- [OWASP HTTP Strict Transport Security Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/HTTP_Strict_Transport_Security_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-319: Cleartext Transmission of Sensitive Information](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/319.html)\n- [Requests: SSL Cert Verification](https://requests.readthedocs.io/en/latest/user/advanced/#ssl-cert-verification)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-319",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/319.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "3.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-319"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "22a0f646-943b-3fd3-993a-297de101e36a",
              "name": "Sql Injection Via String Formatting",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nSQL injection in a database execute call. This code builds an UPDATE statement by inserting password and username directly into the SQL string with .format() and then passes the resulting text to execute.\n\nIn Python DB-API code, string formatting does not protect SQL commands from attacker-controlled input. A crafted username or password can break out of the quoted value, alter the query, or affect unintended rows. The fix is to keep SQL text static and pass user-supplied values separately as query parameters so the database driver handles escaping and binding safely.\n\nFor the sink shown here, replace the formatted SQL string with a parameterized UPDATE statement and provide password and username in the parameter tuple. This preserves the intended query structure and prevents data from being interpreted as SQL code.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not assemble SQL statements with f-strings, percent formatting, .format(), or string concatenation when any part of the statement contains variable data. Use the parameter style required by the Python database driver and pass values through the second argument to execute or executemany. Keep the SQL command text constant, validate input according to business rules, and apply least-privilege database permissions so a single query cannot cause unnecessary damage if abused.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nsql = \"UPDATE users SET password = ? WHERE username = ?\"\nc.execute(sql, (password, username))\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nimport sqlite3\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: SQL Injection](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/SQL_Injection)\n- [OWASP SQL Injection Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/SQL_Injection_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-89: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an SQL Command](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html)\n- [Python sqlite3 documentation](https://docs.python.org/3/library/sqlite3.html)\n- [PEP 249 - Python Database API Specification v2.0](https://peps.python.org/pep-0249/)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-89",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-89"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "28df7bb0-3233-331b-b390-448242299ead",
              "name": "Insecure Cookie Storage Without Signing or Encryption",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThis is an unsigned client-side session cookie issue. In this Python code, application state is converted to JSON, base64-encoded, and written directly into a cookie. Base64 is only an encoding step; it does not provide integrity or confidentiality, so a client can decode, modify, and replay the value.\n\nIf the application later trusts this cookie to identify the user or restore session state, an attacker can forge values such as username or other privileges. The fix is to stop storing trusted state in a raw cookie and instead use a server-side session identifier, or at minimum sign the cookie with a server-held secret and set secure cookie attributes.\n\nFor the sink shown here, the most direct remediation is to replace the serialized JSON cookie with a server-generated opaque session token and keep the actual session data on the server. If a lightweight signed cookie is required, use a well-tested signing library and never keep secrets in source code.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not treat JSON plus base64 as protection for cookie data. Store authentication and authorization state on the server and send only an unpredictable session identifier to the client. If client-side state must be used, protect it with authenticated signing or authenticated encryption using a secret loaded from environment or dedicated key management, not hardcoded in source.\n\nAlways set cookie defenses appropriate for session tokens: HttpOnly to reduce script access, Secure to require HTTPS, and SameSite to limit cross-site request exposure. Keep cookie contents minimal, rotate session identifiers after authentication events, and invalidate server-side session records on logout or timeout.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nimport secrets\n\n# Store session state server-side and send only an opaque session id.\nsession_id = secrets.token_urlsafe(32)\nserver_sessions[session_id] = {\"username\": username}\n\nresponse.set_cookie(\n    \"vulpy_session\",\n    session_id,\n    httponly=True,\n    secure=True,\n    samesite=\"Lax\"\n)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nimport secrets\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Secure Cookie Attribute](https://owasp.org/www-community/controls/SecureCookieAttribute)\n- [OWASP Session Management Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Session_Management_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-565: Reliance on Cookies without Validation and Integrity Checking](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/565.html)\n- [itsdangerous Documentation](https://itsdangerous.palletsprojects.com/)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-565",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/565.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-565"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "329b7eba-ab6c-3355-b6fa-052c713a84b9",
              "name": "Sql Injection Via String Formatting",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nSQL injection in database execution. This code builds an INSERT statement by interpolating Python values directly into the SQL string before passing it to execute(). Even when some current values are constants or expected to be application-controlled, this pattern allows untrusted input such as username to alter the query structure if it reaches this sink.\n\nIn Python DB-API code, values must be supplied separately from the SQL text so the database driver can bind them as data instead of parsing them as SQL. For this INSERT, replace string formatting with placeholders and pass a parameter tuple to execute(). This keeps quoting and escaping in the driver and prevents attacker-controlled input from changing the statement.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not compose SQL with %, .format(), f-strings, or string concatenation. Use the parameter style required by the Python database driver and pass user-supplied values in the parameters argument to execute() or executemany(). Keep SQL structure static, validate input according to business rules before database use, and use least-privilege database accounts so a successful injection has limited impact. If this code runs on a driver other than sqlite3, keep the same approach but use that driver's placeholder syntax, such as %s for psycopg2 or mysqlclient.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nsql = (\n    \"INSERT INTO users \"\n    \"(username, password, salt, failures, mfa_enabled, mfa_secret) \"\n    \"VALUES (?, ?, ?, ?, ?, ?)\"\n)\nparams = (username, '', '', 0, 0, '')\nc.execute(sql, params)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nimport sqlite3\n# For PostgreSQL drivers such as psycopg2, use that driver's parameter style instead of ? placeholders.\n# import psycopg2\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: SQL Injection](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/SQL_Injection)\n- [OWASP SQL Injection Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/SQL_Injection_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-89: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an SQL Command](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html)\n- [Python sqlite3 documentation](https://docs.python.org/3/library/sqlite3.html)\n- [psycopg2 parameter binding documentation](https://www.psycopg.org/docs/usage.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-89",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-89"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "37edff6f-5d83-3078-80c5-aa0f2ffb8867",
              "name": "Insecure Authentication Using Header-Derived Tokens",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThis is an improper authentication issue: the application trusts an API key taken directly from a request header and derives the caller identity from filesystem state. In Python, using a glob pattern built from request data to locate a file under /tmp and then extracting the username from the filename makes authentication dependent on attacker-controlled input and temporary files rather than on a verifiable credential.\n\nThis pattern is unsafe for two reasons. First, the header value is not cryptographically validated, so possession of a matching string is treated as identity without checking signature, expiration, revocation, or server-side ownership. Second, embedding the header value into a filesystem search creates a fragile authentication mechanism that can be bypassed or manipulated through predictable filenames, temporary-file tampering, wildcard interactions, and race conditions. The fix is to validate a signed token or perform a constant-time lookup of a server-issued API key in a trusted data store, then obtain the subject from the validated record instead of from a filename.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not use request-derived values to build filesystem patterns for authentication or derive user identity from filenames. Treat API keys and bearer tokens as credentials that must be validated against a trusted authority. For opaque API keys, store a server-generated value or a keyed hash in a database, compare with hmac.compare_digest, enforce revocation and rotation, and map the validated credential to a subject record. For signed tokens, use a well-supported library to verify the signature, issuer, audience, and expiration before trusting any identity claims. Keep authentication state out of world-writable temporary directories such as /tmp, and return 401 on missing or invalid credentials.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nimport hmac\nimport sqlite3\nfrom flask import abort, g, request\n\nDB_PATH = \"app.db\"\n\n\ndef get_authenticated_subject():\n    api_key = request.headers.get(\"X-APIKEY\")\n    if not api_key:\n        abort(401)\n\n    conn = sqlite3.connect(DB_PATH)\n    conn.row_factory = sqlite3.Row\n    try:\n        row = conn.execute(\n            \"SELECT subject, api_key_hash, revoked FROM api_keys WHERE revoked = 0\"\n        ).fetchall()\n    finally:\n        conn.close()\n\n    for record in row:\n        if hmac.compare_digest(record[\"api_key_hash\"], api_key):\n            g.subject = record[\"subject\"]\n            return record[\"subject\"]\n\n    abort(401)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nFlask\nitsdangerous\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP API Security Top 10 2023 - Broken Authentication](https://owasp.org/API-Security/editions/2023/en/0xa2-broken-authentication/)\n- [OWASP Authentication Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Authentication_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-287: Improper Authentication](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/287.html)\n- [Python hmac module documentation](https://docs.python.org/3/library/hmac.html)\n- [itsdangerous documentation](https://itsdangerous.palletsprojects.com/)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-287",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/287.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-287"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "38cd48cb-eb70-31c6-bbdf-90e8253d959b",
              "name": "Missing CSRF Protection In State-Changing Route",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-site request forgery protection missing on a state-changing Flask route. This endpoint accepts POST form data and performs a sensitive action, but there is no visible CSRF validation before creating the user record.\n\nIn Flask, a route that changes application state based on browser-submitted cookies or session context should require a per-request CSRF token. Without that check, another site can cause a victim's browser to submit a forged POST request to /create. The most reliable fix for this route is to enable framework-level CSRF protection and include the token in the rendered form so POST requests are rejected unless they originate from the legitimate application flow.\n\nFor this specific handler, initialize CSRF protection once for the app, keep the POST logic in place, and render a hidden CSRF field in the form template. If this endpoint is intentionally exempt from session-based browser use, then explicitly require a non-cookie authentication mechanism instead; otherwise, protect the route with CSRF validation.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nUse Flask-WTF or equivalent middleware to enforce CSRF validation on all state-changing form routes by default, rather than adding ad hoc checks in individual handlers. Ensure every HTML form includes the CSRF token field and that the application has a strong SECRET_KEY configured. Prefer validate_on_submit() with FlaskForm objects for POST handling, and reserve CSRF exemptions only for endpoints that are not used by browsers and that require explicit token-based authentication. Origin or Referer checks can add defense in depth, but they should not replace CSRF tokens for normal browser form submissions.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom flask import Flask, flash, redirect, render_template, request, session, Blueprint\nfrom flask_wtf import CSRFProtect\nfrom flask_wtf import FlaskForm\nfrom wtforms import PasswordField, StringField\nfrom wtforms.validators import DataRequired\n\napp = Flask(__name__)\napp.config[\"SECRET_KEY\"] = \"replace-with-a-strong-random-secret\"\ncsrf = CSRFProtect(app)\n\nmod_user = Blueprint(\"mod_user\", __name__)\n\nclass CreateUserForm(FlaskForm):\n    username = StringField(\"username\", validators=[DataRequired()])\n    password = PasswordField(\"password\", validators=[DataRequired()])\n\n@mod_user.route('/create', methods=['GET', 'POST'])\ndef do_create():\n    session.pop('username', None)\n    form = CreateUserForm()\n\n    if form.validate_on_submit():\n        username = form.username.data\n        password = form.password.data\n\n        libuser.create(username, password)\n        flash(\"User created. Please login.\")\n        return redirect('/user/login')\n\n    if request.method == 'POST':\n        flash(\"Please, complete username and password\")\n\n    return render_template('user.create.html', form=form)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nFlask-WTF\nWTForms\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/csrf)\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Request Forgery Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross-Site_Request_Forgery_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [Flask-WTF CSRF Protection](https://flask-wtf.readthedocs.io/en/1.2.x/csrf/)\n- [CWE-352: Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-352",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-352"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "3abff929-ab68-3bb1-a6a0-29b606b74141",
              "name": "Insecure Usage Of Temp File Or Directory",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nInsecure temporary file usage. Writing directly to a predictable path under /tmp can let other local users interfere with the file through pre-creation, symlinks, or race conditions.\n\nIn Python, open('/tmp/acme.pub', 'wb') creates or truncates a file at a well-known shared location without securely reserving the name first. On multi-user systems this can expose data, overwrite unintended files, or allow an attacker to redirect writes to another path. For temporary output, use the standard tempfile module to create the file securely with restrictive permissions and an unpredictable name.\n\nFor the sink shown here, replace the hard-coded /tmp path with tempfile.NamedTemporaryFile or mkstemp, and keep the file descriptor ownership within the process. If the file must later be renamed to a final destination, create it securely first and then move it with an atomic operation.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nAvoid constructing temporary file paths manually in shared directories such as /tmp. Use Python's tempfile APIs, which generate unpredictable names and create files with safer defaults. Prefer mkstemp when you need a path and descriptor, or NamedTemporaryFile when automatic lifecycle management fits the use case.\n\nIf a stable output filename is required, write to a securely created temporary file first and then publish it with os.replace to minimize race conditions. Also keep temporary files readable only by the current user, avoid following symlinks implicitly, and clean up temporary artifacts promptly after use.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nimport os\nimport tempfile\n\nfd, temp_path = tempfile.mkstemp(suffix=\".pub\")\ntry:\n    with os.fdopen(fd, \"wb\") as out:\n        out.write(public_key_bytes)\n\n    # If needed, move temp_path to a final destination with os.replace().\nfinally:\n    if os.path.exists(temp_path):\n        os.remove(temp_path)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nimport os\nimport tempfile\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-377: Insecure Temporary File](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html)\n- [CWE-379: Creation of Temporary File in Directory with Insecure Permissions](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/379.html)\n- [Python tempfile — Generate temporary files and directories securely](https://docs.python.org/3/library/tempfile.html)\n- [OWASP: Insecure Temporary File](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Insecure_Temporary_File)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-377",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html"
                  },
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-379",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/379.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-377",
                  "CWE-379"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "3c9566d8-c680-3db8-b643-79579cc1051c",
              "name": "Missing CSRF Protection In State-Changing Route",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-site request forgery protection is missing on a state-changing Flask endpoint. This POST route accepts form data and performs an authenticated action using the current session, but there is no visible CSRF token validation before calling the write operation.\n\nIn Flask, a user who is already logged in can be tricked into submitting a forged POST request from another site. Because the browser automatically includes the victim's session cookies, the application may create a post as that user without their intent. For this route, protect the form submission with a server-validated CSRF token and reject requests that do not present a valid token.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nEnable CSRF protection globally for the Flask application so all unsafe methods such as POST, PUT, PATCH, and DELETE are checked automatically. If the route is backed by an HTML form, include the CSRF token field in the rendered form and ensure the application uses a strong secret key for token signing. For endpoints that are not browser form submissions, require a dedicated anti-CSRF token or use a design that does not rely on ambient session cookies.\n\nAs an additional defense, configure session cookies with SameSite and Secure attributes and validate Origin or Referer headers for authenticated state-changing requests where appropriate. Do not rely on request.method checks alone, because they do not verify request intent.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom flask import Blueprint, g, redirect, request\nfrom flask_wtf.csrf import CSRFProtect\n\ncsrf = CSRFProtect()\nmod_posts = Blueprint('posts', __name__)\n\n@mod_posts.route('/', methods=['POST'])\ndef do_create():\n    if 'username' not in g.session:\n        return redirect('/user/login')\n\n    username = g.session['username']\n    text = request.form.get('text', '')\n\n    libposts.post(username, text)\n    return redirect('/')\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nFlask-WTF\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/csrf)\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Request Forgery Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross-Site_Request_Forgery_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [Flask-WTF CSRF Protection](https://flask-wtf.readthedocs.io/en/1.2.x/csrf/)\n- [CWE-352: Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-352",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-352"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "42df2164-279b-3d58-9e07-0fd2b1f9117a",
              "name": "Missing CSRF Protection In State-Changing Route",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-site request forgery protection is missing on a state-changing Flask route. This login handler accepts POSTed form data and creates an authenticated session, but there is no visible CSRF token validation and no Origin or Referer verification before processing the request.\n\nIn Flask, a browser will automatically include cookies with cross-site requests unless the application explicitly defends against them. That allows an attacker to cause a victim's browser to submit a forged POST to this endpoint and potentially bind the victim to an attacker-chosen account or interfere with the login flow. Protect this route by enabling framework-level CSRF validation for form submissions and by rejecting cross-origin POST requests that do not come from the application's own origin.\n\nFor this sink, the most reliable fix is to initialize CSRF protection for the application, render a hidden CSRF token in the login form, and validate the request before reading form fields. As a defense in depth measure, verify the Origin header on POST requests and ensure the session cookie is configured with Secure, HttpOnly, and an appropriate SameSite policy.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nUse framework-managed CSRF protection for every form-handling POST, PUT, PATCH, and DELETE route that changes authentication state or server state. In Flask, apply CSRFProtect at the application or blueprint level so validation happens automatically before the handler processes request data, and include the CSRF token in the rendered HTML form.\n\nTreat Origin or Referer validation as defense in depth rather than the only control. Also harden session cookies with Secure, HttpOnly, and SameSite, prefer HTTPS everywhere, and avoid exempting authentication endpoints from CSRF checks because login CSRF can still create security and user-session integrity problems.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom urllib.parse import urlparse\n\nfrom flask import Flask, abort, flash, make_response, redirect, render_template, request, session\nfrom flask_wtf import CSRFProtect\n\napp = Flask(__name__)\napp.config[\"SECRET_KEY\"] = \"replace-with-a-strong-random-secret\"\napp.config[\"WTF_CSRF_TIME_LIMIT\"] = 3600\napp.config[\"SESSION_COOKIE_SECURE\"] = True\napp.config[\"SESSION_COOKIE_HTTPONLY\"] = True\napp.config[\"SESSION_COOKIE_SAMESITE\"] = \"Lax\"\n\ncsrf = CSRFProtect(app)\n\n\ndef _same_origin(req):\n    origin = req.headers.get(\"Origin\")\n    if not origin:\n        return True\n    expected = req.host_url.rstrip(\"/\")\n    return origin.rstrip(\"/\") == expected\n\n\n@mod_user.route('/login', methods=['GET', 'POST'])\ndef do_login():\n    session.pop('username', None)\n\n    if request.method == 'POST':\n        if not _same_origin(request):\n            abort(403)\n\n        username = request.form.get('username', '')\n        password = request.form.get('password', '')\n        otp = request.form.get('otp', '')\n\n        username = libuser.login(username, password)\n\n        if not username:\n            flash(\"Invalid user or password\")\n            return render_template('user.login.mfa.html')\n\n        if libmfa.mfa_is_enabled(username):\n            if not libmfa.mfa_validate(username, otp):\n                flash(\"Invalid OTP\")\n                return render_template('user.login.mfa.html')\n\n        response = make_response(redirect('/'))\n        response = libsession.create(request=request, response=response, username=username)\n        return response\n\n    return render_template('user.login.mfa.html')\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nFlask-WTF\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Cross Site Request Forgery](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/csrf)\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Request Forgery Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross-Site_Request_Forgery_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-352: Cross-Site Request Forgery](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html)\n- [Flask-WTF CSRF Protection](https://flask-wtf.readthedocs.io/en/1.2.x/csrf/)\n- [Flask Security Considerations](https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/web-security/)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-352",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-352"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "43b0aaf2-a164-3bd6-92ad-143ecf2443d8",
              "name": "Missing CSRF Protection In State-Changing Route",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-site request forgery in a state-changing Flask route. This POST handler accepts form data and performs a write operation using the authenticated session, but it does not show any CSRF token validation before calling the state-changing function.\n\nIn Flask, a browser will automatically include the user’s session cookie on cross-site requests unless additional protections are enforced. That means another site can cause a logged-in user’s browser to submit a forged POST request to this endpoint, creating content on the user’s behalf. For this route, protect the form submission with server-side CSRF validation and reject requests that do not present a valid token.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nEnable CSRF protection at the Flask application level so all unsafe methods such as POST, PUT, PATCH, and DELETE are validated automatically. For HTML forms, include the generated CSRF token in the form and let Flask-WTF validate it on submission. Keep CSRF validation on the server side and do not rely on hidden fields alone.\n\nFor sensitive state-changing routes, also verify same-origin request metadata such as the Origin header, and fall back to Referer checks only when needed. Use session.get() instead of direct indexing to avoid unexpected key errors, restrict the route to the exact path you intend to expose, and ensure the session cookie is configured securely with Secure, HttpOnly, and an appropriate SameSite policy.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom flask import Flask, redirect, request, session, abort\nfrom flask_wtf.csrf import CSRFProtect\n\napp = Flask(__name__)\napp.config[\"SECRET_KEY\"] = \"change-this-secret-key\"\ncsrf = CSRFProtect(app)\n\n@mod_welcome.route('/post', methods=['POST'])\ndef do_post():\n    if not session.get('username'):\n        return redirect('/user/login')\n\n    username = session['username']\n    text = request.form.get('text', '')\n\n    origin = request.headers.get('Origin')\n    if origin and origin.rstrip('/') != request.host_url.rstrip('/'):\n        abort(403)\n\n    post(username, text)\n    return redirect('/')\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nFlask\nFlask-WTF\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Request Forgery](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/csrf)\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Request Forgery Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross-Site_Request_Forgery_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-352: Cross-Site Request Forgery](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html)\n- [Flask-WTF CSRF Protection](https://flask-wtf.readthedocs.io/en/1.2.x/csrf/)\n- [Flask Security Considerations](https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/latest/web-security/)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-352",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-352"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "455b8595-f03d-32c2-92fa-f948c17d8314",
              "name": "Insecure Usage Of Temp File Or Directory",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nInsecure temporary file handling. This code reads sensitive material from a hard-coded path under /tmp, which is a shared world-writable directory on many systems. In Python, opening a predictable filename in that location can expose the application to symlink attacks, file replacement, race conditions, or unintended disclosure if another user or process can create or modify the file first.\n\nFor a key file such as /tmp/acme.key, the safer approach is to avoid predictable temporary paths entirely and create the file with the tempfile module using restrictive permissions. If the file must persist long enough to be reopened, create it with tempfile.NamedTemporaryFile or tempfile.mkstemp, limit access to the current process, and delete it as soon as it is no longer needed. If the data does not need a filesystem path, keep it in memory instead of writing it to /tmp.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not use fixed filenames in shared temporary directories for sensitive files. Create temporary files with Python's tempfile APIs so the runtime chooses a unique name and the file is created atomically. Restrict permissions to the current user, keep the lifetime of the file as short as possible, and remove it immediately after use. For secrets such as private keys, prefer in-memory handling when the consuming API allows bytes or file-like objects instead of a filesystem path.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nimport os\nimport tempfile\n\nfd, key_path = tempfile.mkstemp(prefix=\"acme_\", suffix=\".key\")\ntry:\n    with os.fdopen(fd, \"wb\") as key_file:\n        key_file.write(key_bytes)\n\n    with open(key_path, \"rb\") as key_file:\n        key_data = key_file.read()\nfinally:\n    if os.path.exists(key_path):\n        os.remove(key_path)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nimport os\nimport tempfile\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-377: Insecure Temporary File](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html)\n- [CWE-378: Creation of Temporary File With Insecure Permissions](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/378.html)\n- [Python tempfile module](https://docs.python.org/3/library/tempfile.html)\n- [OWASP: Insecure Temporary File](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Insecure_Temporary_File)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-377",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html"
                  },
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-378",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/378.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-377",
                  "CWE-378"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "4bc5d952-6423-3b33-b913-4b1c5d4ef11b",
              "name": "Flask App Running In Debug Mode",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThis is an enabled debug mode vulnerability. In Python Flask applications, starting the development server with debug mode turned on exposes interactive debugging features that are not safe for deployed environments.\n\nIn this sink, the application is launched with app.run(debug=True, host='127.0.1.1', ssl_context=('/tmp/acme.cert', '/tmp/acme.key')). Even when TLS is configured and the bind address is loopback-like, debug mode still enables the Werkzeug debugger and verbose error handling. If the service is ever exposed through port forwarding, a reverse proxy, container networking, or misconfiguration, an attacker may gain access to sensitive stack traces or interactive code execution. The fix is to disable debug mode and run the application with production-safe settings.\n\nFor Flask, keep debug disabled in runtime code, do not hardcode development flags in the application entry point, and rely on environment-specific configuration. Use a production WSGI server for deployed workloads and keep certificate handling and network exposure separate from development-only debugging behavior.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDisable Flask debug mode in all deployed environments and remove hardcoded debug=True from the application startup path. Keep development-only behavior behind environment-based configuration that defaults to secure values. Do not rely on loopback binding or TLS alone to make the debugger safe, because container publishing, SSH tunnels, reverse proxies, and network policy mistakes can still expose the service. For production, serve the Flask app with a WSGI server such as gunicorn or uWSGI, keep Werkzeug's debugger disabled, and restrict operational error details to server-side logs instead of user-facing responses.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom flask import Flask\n\napp = Flask(__name__)\n\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    app.run(debug=False, host=\"127.0.1.1\", ssl_context=(\"/tmp/acme.cert\", \"/tmp/acme.key\"))\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nflask\ngunicorn\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [Flask Documentation: Debugging Application Errors](https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/debugging/)\n- [Werkzeug Documentation: Debugger](https://werkzeug.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/debug/)\n- [OWASP Top 10](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/)\n- [CWE-489: Active Debug Code](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/489.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-489",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/489.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-489"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "4be6cc33-b756-3ac6-a0ea-fe45725f83d7",
              "name": "Insecure Usage Of Temp File Or Directory",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nInsecure temporary file usage. In Python, opening a predictable path under /tmp can expose the program to symlink attacks, file substitution, and unintended disclosure because /tmp is typically shared by multiple users and processes.\n\nThe shown code reads from a fixed filename in /tmp. An attacker who can create, replace, or link that path before the file is opened may cause the application to read untrusted content or a different file than intended. Mitigate this by avoiding hard-coded temporary paths and by creating or accessing temporary files through Python's tempfile APIs, which generate unique names and apply safer permissions.\n\nIf the file must persist briefly, create it with tempfile.NamedTemporaryFile or place it in a directory created by tempfile.TemporaryDirectory and then open it by the returned path. If this code is only trying to read application data, store that data in an application-controlled directory instead of a world-writable temporary location.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not use predictable filenames in shared temporary directories such as /tmp. Create temporary files and directories with the tempfile module so the operating system chooses a unique path and restrictive permissions. If the code is consuming an existing file, move it to an application-owned directory with controlled permissions instead of relying on a shared temporary location. When possible, keep temporary data open through the file handle returned by tempfile APIs rather than reopening by name.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom tempfile import NamedTemporaryFile\n\nwith NamedTemporaryFile(mode=\"w+t\", delete=False, encoding=\"utf-8\") as tmp:\n    tmp.write(\"example content\\n\")\n    temp_path = tmp.name\n\nwith open(temp_path, encoding=\"utf-8\") as f:\n    data = f.read()\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\ntempfile\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-377: Insecure Temporary File](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html)\n- [CWE-378: Creation of Temporary File With Insecure Permissions](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/378.html)\n- [Python tempfile — Generate temporary files and directories securely](https://docs.python.org/3/library/tempfile.html)\n- [OWASP: Insecure Temporary File](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Insecure_Temporary_File)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-377",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html"
                  },
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-378",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/378.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-377",
                  "CWE-378"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "4dd49418-d538-387d-9f7b-7a5ac9b7ff8b",
              "name": "Insecure Usage Of Temp File Or Directory",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nInsecure temporary file handling. This code stores a sensitive value in a predictable path under /tmp, which is a shared world-writable directory on many systems. In Python, creating or referencing a fixed filename such as /tmp/supersecret.txt exposes the secret to symlink attacks, file replacement, accidental disclosure, and permission mistakes.\n\nFor an API key, avoid hard-coded temporary paths entirely when possible. If a temporary file is required, create it with Python's tempfile APIs so the filename is unpredictable and the file is created securely with restricted permissions. Prefer a private temporary directory or a named temporary file opened by the process itself, write the secret through the returned handle, and remove it as soon as it is no longer needed.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not place secrets in predictable filenames under /tmp or other shared temporary locations. Use tempfile.NamedTemporaryFile or tempfile.TemporaryDirectory to let the operating system create a unique path securely. Keep the file lifetime as short as possible, restrict access to the current process, and delete the file after use. Where the receiving API allows it, prefer passing the secret in memory instead of writing it to disk. Also avoid logging the temporary path if it reveals the presence or purpose of sensitive material.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom pathlib import Path\nfrom tempfile import NamedTemporaryFile\n\nwith NamedTemporaryFile(mode=\"w\", encoding=\"utf-8\", delete=False) as tmp:\n    tmp.write(api_key)\n    api_key_file = Path(tmp.name)\n\ntry:\n    use_api_key_file(api_key_file)\nfinally:\n    api_key_file.unlink(missing_ok=True)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nfrom pathlib import Path\nfrom tempfile import NamedTemporaryFile\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-377: Insecure Temporary File](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html)\n- [CWE-379: Creation of Temporary File in Directory with Insecure Permissions](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/379.html)\n- [Python tempfile module](https://docs.python.org/3/library/tempfile.html)\n- [OWASP: Insecure Temporary File](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Insecure_Temporary_File)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-377",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html"
                  },
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-379",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/379.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-377",
                  "CWE-379"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "503f541e-1c03-3b09-a96c-20998c31a0ef",
              "name": "Missing Function Level Access Control",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nMissing function-level access control. This view processes a session cookie and returns user identity data, but it does not enforce authentication or authorization at the route level. Relying on ad hoc cookie handling inside the function is weaker than using framework-supported access-control checks before the handler runs.\n\nIn Python web applications, access control should be explicit and centralized. Even though the code decrypts a token and compares the country to the client IP-derived location, that logic is not a substitute for authentication and authorization. A valid cookie alone should not grant access unless the framework has established an authenticated user session and the handler verifies that the caller is allowed to access this function.\n\nProtect the endpoint with authentication decorators and perform authorization checks using the current authenticated principal. Keep session validation in the framework session layer instead of manually parsing cookies in each view. If location checks are required as a defense-in-depth signal, treat them as supplemental risk controls rather than the primary gate for access.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nRequire authentication before the view executes by using the web framework's authentication decorator or middleware. After authentication, enforce authorization for the specific action or resource, such as checking a role, permission, or object-level policy. Do not treat a decrypted client cookie or network-derived attribute such as country as the primary access-control decision.\n\nUse secure server-managed sessions and retrieve identity from the authenticated user context instead of manually decoding identity data in each handler. Return 401 for unauthenticated requests and 403 for authenticated users who lack permission. Keep authorization logic consistent across routes, ideally through reusable decorators, middleware, or a policy layer.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom flask import abort\nfrom flask_login import current_user, login_required\n\n@login_required\ndef load(request):\n    if not current_user.is_authenticated:\n        abort(401)\n\n    if not getattr(current_user, \"can_view_profile\", False):\n        abort(403)\n\n    return {\n        \"username\": current_user.username,\n        \"country\": current_user.country,\n    }\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nFlask-Login\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Broken Access Control](https://owasp.org/www-community/Broken_Access_Control)\n- [OWASP Authorization Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Authorization_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-306: Missing Authentication for Critical Function](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/306.html)\n- [CWE-862: Missing Authorization](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/862.html)\n- [Flask-Login Documentation](https://flask-login.readthedocs.io/)\n- [Flask View Decorators](https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/patterns/viewdecorators/)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-306",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/306.html"
                  },
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-862",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/862.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-306",
                  "CWE-862"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "514a52f7-9e84-3b1e-be4a-b0519038bc0f",
              "name": "GET Route Performs State-Changing Action",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nState-changing action exposed via GET with missing CSRF protection. In Python web applications, a route that disables MFA must not be reachable with GET because browsers, crawlers, prefetchers, and cross-site requests can trigger GET endpoints without the user's intent.\n\nIn the shown Flask-style route, visiting /disable immediately calls libmfa.mfa_disable(...) for the authenticated session and then redirects. That allows an attacker to embed a link, image, or auto-submitting page that causes a logged-in user to disable MFA. Change the route to POST-only and require a validated CSRF token before performing the action.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nUse GET only for safe, read-only operations. Any endpoint that creates, updates, deletes, or disables security settings should require POST, PUT, PATCH, or DELETE as appropriate, and enforce CSRF validation tied to the user session. For sensitive account actions such as MFA changes, also require re-authentication or step-up verification when practical.\n\nIn Flask applications, enable framework-supported CSRF protection globally, render a form containing the CSRF token, and reject requests with missing or invalid tokens. Avoid performing state changes during redirects or from query-string driven links. Ensure templates and client code submit the action as a form POST rather than a simple hyperlink.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom flask import Blueprint, g, redirect, url_for, abort, render_template\nfrom flask_wtf import FlaskForm, CSRFProtect\nfrom wtforms import SubmitField\n\ncsrf = CSRFProtect()\nmod_mfa = Blueprint('mod_mfa', __name__)\n\n\nclass DisableMFAForm(FlaskForm):\n    submit = SubmitField('Disable MFA')\n\n\n@mod_mfa.route('/disable', methods=['POST'])\ndef do_mfa_disable():\n    if 'username' not in g.session:\n        return redirect('/user/login')\n\n    form = DisableMFAForm()\n    if not form.validate_on_submit():\n        abort(400)\n\n    libmfa.mfa_disable(g.session['username'])\n    return redirect('/mfa/')\n\n\n@mod_mfa.route('/disable', methods=['GET'])\ndef disable_mfa_confirm():\n    if 'username' not in g.session:\n        return redirect('/user/login')\n\n    form = DisableMFAForm()\n    return render_template('mfa_disable_confirm.html', form=form)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nFlask-WTF\nWTForms\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/csrf)\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Request Forgery Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross-Site_Request_Forgery_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-352: Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html)\n- [Flask-WTF CSRF Protection](https://flask-wtf.readthedocs.io/en/1.2.x/csrf/)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-352",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-352"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "532f2b44-53c9-3901-8c49-60c70b2a79e0",
              "name": "Missing CSRF Protection In State-Changing Route",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-site request forgery protection is missing on a state-changing Flask route. This handler accepts POST form input, changes session state, and performs authentication-related work without visible CSRF validation, so a malicious site can cause a victim's browser to submit the request with the victim's cookies attached.\n\nIn Flask, protecting routes like this should be done at the framework or form layer rather than by relying on client behavior. For the shown /create endpoint, add server-side CSRF validation to the POST flow and include the CSRF token in the rendered form. If this endpoint is intended only for browser form submissions, keep the route limited to POST for submission handling and reject requests with invalid or missing CSRF tokens.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nEnable CSRF protection globally for the Flask application using Flask-WTF or an equivalent server-side mechanism, set a strong SECRET_KEY, and ensure every HTML form that performs login, account creation, password changes, or other state-changing actions includes a CSRF token that is validated on POST. For template rendering, use a FlaskForm and render the hidden token field so protection is applied consistently.\n\nFor routes intended for browser use, do not rely on Origin or Referer checks as the primary defense; they can be used as an additional verification layer, but the main control should be a per-request CSRF token bound to the user session. If the endpoint is actually an API and not a browser form target, prefer token-based authentication without cookie ambient authority and disable session-based cross-site requests.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom flask import Blueprint, redirect, render_template, request, session\nfrom flask_wtf import FlaskForm, CSRFProtect\nfrom wtforms import PasswordField, StringField\nfrom wtforms.validators import DataRequired, Email\n\nmod_user = Blueprint('user', __name__)\ncsrf = CSRFProtect()\n\nclass CreateUserForm(FlaskForm):\n    username = StringField('username', validators=[DataRequired()])\n    password = PasswordField('password', validators=[DataRequired()])\n    email = StringField('email', validators=[DataRequired(), Email()])\n\n@mod_user.route('/create', methods=['GET', 'POST'])\ndef do_create():\n    form = CreateUserForm()\n\n    if form.validate_on_submit():\n        session.pop('username', None)\n\n        username = form.username.data\n        password = form.password.data\n        email = form.email.data\n\n        session['username'] = libuser.login(username, password)\n\n        if session['username']:\n            return redirect('/')\n\n    return render_template('user.create.html', form=form)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nFlask-WTF\nWTForms\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Cross Site Request Forgery](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/csrf)\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Request Forgery Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross-Site_Request_Forgery_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-352: Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html)\n- [Flask-WTF CSRF Protection](https://flask-wtf.readthedocs.io/en/1.2.x/csrf/)\n- [Flask Patterns for Forms](https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/patterns/wtforms/)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-352",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-352"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "626f0446-109a-3f86-bd97-2ab5fe7e40f3",
              "name": "SQL Injection Via Raw SQL Query Concatenation",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nSQL injection in database query construction. This code builds an SQL statement by interpolating username and password directly into the query string before sending it to the database.\n\nIn Python, string formatting does not escape SQL metacharacters safely. An attacker can supply crafted input that changes the meaning of the WHERE clause, bypasses authentication, or exposes data. The fix is to use parameterized queries so the database treats user input strictly as data.\n\nFor the sink shown here, replace string concatenation with DB-API placeholders supported by sqlite3, or use SQLAlchemy bound parameters if this query is executed through SQLAlchemy. This keeps the SQL text static and binds username and password separately at execution time.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nUse parameterized queries for all database access and never compose SQL with format(), f-strings, percent formatting, or concatenation. Keep the SQL structure fixed and pass untrusted values as separate parameters through the database driver.\n\nFor simple Python database code, use the parameter style required by the driver, such as ? for sqlite3. If the application uses SQLAlchemy, prefer the ORM or Core expression APIs, or use text() with named bind parameters instead of embedding values in raw SQL. Also avoid storing plaintext passwords; store password hashes using a dedicated password hashing library and compare hashes during authentication.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nuser = c.execute(\n    \"SELECT * FROM users WHERE username = ? AND password = ?\",\n    (username, password)\n).fetchone()\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nfrom sqlite3 import Connection\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP SQL Injection](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/SQL_Injection)\n- [OWASP SQL Injection Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/SQL_Injection_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-89: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an SQL Command](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html)\n- [Python sqlite3 module documentation](https://docs.python.org/3/library/sqlite3.html)\n- [SQLAlchemy text() and bound parameters](https://docs.sqlalchemy.org/en/20/core/sqlelement.html#sqlalchemy.sql.expression.text)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-89",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-89"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "638bd8d0-7bff-312b-9a8b-43382c87476e",
              "name": "Direct Write To SQL Password Column",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nPlaintext password storage. This code writes the password value directly into the database, which exposes user credentials if the database, backups, logs, or query traces are accessed by an attacker or an unauthorized administrator.\n\nIn Python, the fix is to derive a password hash with a slow password hashing algorithm and store only the derived hash, never the original password. For the sink shown, also replace Python string interpolation in the SQL statement with a parameterized query so the password hash and other values are bound safely instead of embedded into SQL text.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nUse a dedicated password hashing function such as bcrypt, scrypt, Argon2, or PBKDF2 with a unique salt per password and a cost factor appropriate for your environment. Do not encrypt or reversibly encode passwords for storage, and do not store raw passwords anywhere in the application lifecycle beyond the moment needed to verify or hash them.\n\nUse parameterized SQL for inserts and updates instead of building queries with string formatting. Keep password verification centralized in authentication code, support hash upgrades over time, and consider using a separate column name such as password_hash to make the stored value's purpose explicit.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nimport bcrypt\n\npassword_hash = bcrypt.hashpw(password.encode(\"utf-8\"), bcrypt.gensalt()).decode(\"utf-8\")\n\nc.execute(\n    \"INSERT INTO users (username, password, failures, mfa_enabled, mfa_secret) VALUES (?, ?, ?, ?, ?)\",\n    (username, password_hash, 0, 0, \"\")\n)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nbcrypt\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Password Storage Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Password_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-256: Plaintext Storage of a Password](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/256.html)\n- [Python hashlib.pbkdf2_hmac](https://docs.python.org/3/library/hashlib.html#hashlib.pbkdf2_hmac)\n- [Python secrets module](https://docs.python.org/3/library/secrets.html)\n- [bcrypt for Python](https://pypi.org/project/bcrypt/)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-256",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/256.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-256"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "6953c875-f699-37f4-9ba2-645b11f43234",
              "name": "Insecure Usage Of Temp File Or Directory",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nInsecure temporary file handling. Writing sensitive data directly to a predictable path such as /tmp/acme.key in Python can allow other local users or processes to read, replace, or pre-create the file before your code opens it.\n\nOn Unix-like systems, /tmp is typically shared and world-writable. If this file contains key material, an attacker may exploit symlinks, race conditions, or permissive default file modes to disclose or overwrite sensitive content. In this case, the fix is to avoid hard-coded temporary paths and create the file securely with Python's tempfile APIs and restrictive permissions.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nUse Python's tempfile module to create temporary files with unpredictable names and exclusive creation semantics instead of writing to a fixed path under /tmp. When the file contains secrets such as private keys, ensure the mode is restricted to the current user, typically 0o600, and remove the file as soon as it is no longer needed. Avoid following attacker-controlled paths, avoid checking then creating files in separate steps, and prefer APIs that atomically create the file for you.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nimport os\nimport tempfile\n\nfd, temp_path = tempfile.mkstemp(prefix=\"acme_\", suffix=\".key\")\ntry:\n    os.fchmod(fd, 0o600)\n    with os.fdopen(fd, \"wb\") as out:\n        out.write(key_bytes)\nfinally:\n    pass\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nimport os\nimport tempfile\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-377: Insecure Temporary File](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html)\n- [CWE-378: Creation of Temporary File With Insecure Permissions](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/378.html)\n- [Python tempfile — Generate temporary files and directories securely](https://docs.python.org/3/library/tempfile.html)\n- [OWASP: Insecure Temporary File](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Insecure_Temporary_File)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-377",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html"
                  },
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-378",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/378.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-377",
                  "CWE-378"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "6be2be1b-b54d-3d5e-8c29-ee3b3683a916",
              "name": "Insecure Usage Of Temp File Or Directory",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nInsecure temporary file usage. This code starts a Python web application with an SSL certificate and private key loaded from predictable paths under /tmp. Files in shared temporary directories are vulnerable to tampering, replacement, symlink attacks, and unintended disclosure if permissions are not tightly controlled.\n\nIn this sink, the private key path is especially sensitive. An attacker on the same system may be able to pre-create, replace, or read files in /tmp depending on filesystem protections and process privileges. The call also enables debug mode, which is not appropriate for production-facing TLS service startup. Store certificate material in a dedicated non-temporary directory with restrictive permissions, and run the server without debug enabled.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not place certificates, private keys, session files, or other security-sensitive assets in world-writable temporary directories such as /tmp. Use a dedicated application-owned directory outside temporary storage, set ownership to the service account, and restrict the private key to owner-only permissions such as 0o600. If temporary files are truly required elsewhere in the application, create them with Python's tempfile module and keep handles open to reduce race conditions.\n\nDisable debug mode for deployed services. Prefer terminating TLS in a production-grade web server or reverse proxy, or at minimum ensure the Python process reads key material from stable, access-controlled paths. Validate file existence, type, and permissions before starting the listener so the application fails closed when TLS assets are misconfigured.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom pathlib import Path\nimport os\n\nfrom flask import Flask\n\napp = Flask(__name__)\n\ncert_path = Path(\"/etc/myapp/tls/server.crt\")\nkey_path = Path(\"/etc/myapp/tls/server.key\")\n\nfor path in (cert_path, key_path):\n    st = path.stat()\n    if not path.is_file():\n        raise RuntimeError(f\"Missing TLS file: {path}\")\n    if path == key_path and (st.st_mode & 0o077):\n        raise RuntimeError(\"TLS private key permissions must be restricted to the owner\")\n\napp.run(\n    debug=False,\n    host=\"127.0.0.1\",\n    ssl_context=(str(cert_path), str(key_path)),\n)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nfrom pathlib import Path\nimport os\nfrom flask import Flask\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-377: Insecure Temporary File](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html)\n- [CWE-378: Creation of Temporary File With Insecure Permissions](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/378.html)\n- [Python tempfile — Generate temporary files and directories securely](https://docs.python.org/3/library/tempfile.html)\n- [Flask Development Server](https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/server/)\n- [Werkzeug Serving Documentation](https://werkzeug.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/serving/)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-377",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html"
                  },
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-378",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/378.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-377",
                  "CWE-378"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "6be401d7-3597-35f4-a23f-3cf6e295192f",
              "name": "Flask App Running In Debug Mode",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nInsecure debug mode enabled in a production web application. In Python Flask applications, running the development server with debug=True enables interactive debugging features intended only for local development.\n\nWhen debug mode is active, Flask and Werkzeug can expose detailed stack traces, internal application state, configuration values, and an interactive debugger. If this behavior is reachable outside a tightly controlled local development environment, it can lead to information disclosure and arbitrary code execution. In the shown sink, app.run(debug=True, host='127.0.1.1', port=5000, extra_files='csp.txt') explicitly enables that unsafe mode.\n\nDisable debug mode in runtime code and avoid relying on the built-in development server for deployed environments. For this call site, set debug=False, keep development-only reload behavior out of production code, and run the application behind a production WSGI server with configuration controlled by environment-specific settings.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not enable Flask debug mode outside local development. Remove hard-coded debug=True from application code and default to debug=False. Separate development and production configuration with environment variables or dedicated config classes, and do not expose the Werkzeug debugger to users. Use a production-grade WSGI server such as gunicorn or uWSGI for deployment, and restrict any local debugging features to trusted developer machines only. Also avoid development-only options such as automatic reload of extra files in deployed builds unless they are explicitly required and safely controlled.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nimport os\n\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    app.run(\n        debug=False,\n        host=os.getenv(\"FLASK_HOST\", \"127.0.0.1\"),\n        port=int(os.getenv(\"FLASK_PORT\", \"5000\"))\n    )\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nimport os\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [Flask Documentation: Debugging Application Errors](https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/debugging/)\n- [Werkzeug Documentation: Debugger](https://werkzeug.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/debug/)\n- [OWASP Top 10](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/)\n- [CWE-489: Active Debug Code](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/489.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-489",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/489.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-489"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "6fb1b190-c108-3417-a082-3b3bc36e91b2",
              "name": "Missing CSRF Protection In State-Changing Route",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-site request forgery protection is missing on a state-changing POST route. In this Flask handler, a logged-in user's browser can be induced to submit a POST request to the MFA enable endpoint because the route reads form data and changes account state without visible CSRF token enforcement.\n\nFor Python Flask applications, session cookies are sent automatically by the browser, so checking only that the user is logged in does not prove the request originated from your own form. This endpoint enables MFA after validating an OTP, which is still a sensitive state change and should require a per-request CSRF token, with optional Origin or Referer validation as an additional defense.\n\nApply CSRF protection at the framework layer so every unsafe method is covered consistently, and ensure the HTML form that posts otp includes the generated token. If a global solution is not yet available, add a route-level token check and reject requests with missing or invalid tokens before processing the form.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nEnable CSRF protection globally for the Flask application so all state-changing POST, PUT, PATCH, and DELETE routes are covered by default. Use a standard Flask CSRF implementation that binds a server-generated token to the user session and require the token on every HTML form that changes application state.\n\nFor this MFA enable flow, render the token in the form and validate it before reading otp or updating MFA state. Keep the route limited to authenticated users, and add Origin or Referer checks for browser-based form submissions as a secondary control, not a replacement for CSRF tokens. Also ensure session cookies are configured with Secure, HttpOnly, and an appropriate SameSite value to reduce cross-site request risk.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom flask import Blueprint, flash, g, redirect, render_template, request\nfrom flask_wtf import FlaskForm, CSRFProtect\nfrom wtforms import StringField, SubmitField\nfrom wtforms.validators import DataRequired\nimport pyotp\n\ncsrf = CSRFProtect()\nmod_mfa = Blueprint('mod_mfa', __name__)\n\n\nclass MFAEnableForm(FlaskForm):\n    otp = StringField('One-time password', validators=[DataRequired()])\n    submit = SubmitField('Enable MFA')\n\n\n@mod_mfa.route('/', methods=['GET', 'POST'])\ndef do_mfa_enable():\n    if 'username' not in g.session:\n        return redirect('/user/login')\n\n    form = MFAEnableForm()\n\n    if request.method == 'POST':\n        if not form.validate_on_submit():\n            flash('Invalid or missing CSRF token')\n            return redirect('/mfa/')\n\n        secret = libmfa.mfa_get_secret(g.session['username'])\n        totp = pyotp.TOTP(secret)\n\n        if totp.verify(form.otp.data):\n            libmfa.mfa_enable(g.session['username'])\n            return redirect('/mfa/')\n\n        flash('The OTP was incorrect')\n        return redirect('/mfa/')\n\n    return render_template('mfa.enable.html', form=form)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nFlask-WTF\nWTForms\npyotp\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/csrf)\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Request Forgery Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross-Site_Request_Forgery_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-352: Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html)\n- [Flask-WTF CSRF Protection](https://flask-wtf.readthedocs.io/en/1.2.x/csrf/)\n- [Werkzeug Request Referer and Origin Handling](https://werkzeug.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/wrappers/#werkzeug.wrappers.request.Request.referrer)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-352",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-352"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "72bf6ac1-3fc1-3f8e-b996-1353c6a2ec61",
              "name": "SQL Injection Via Raw SQL Query Concatenation",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nSQL injection through string-formatted database queries. This code builds an INSERT statement by interpolating Python values directly into SQL before calling execute(). If username or password contains quotes or crafted SQL fragments, the database may parse attacker-controlled input as part of the command instead of as data.\n\nIn Python DB-API code, values must be passed separately from the SQL text so the driver can bind them safely. For the sink shown here, replace %-formatting with a parameterized query and provide the values as a tuple or mapping. Keep constants such as failure counters and MFA flags as bound parameters or hardcoded literals, but never concatenate untrusted input into the SQL string.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nUse parameterized queries for every database operation, including INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE, and SELECT. In Python, follow the parameter style required by the active DB driver instead of assembling SQL with %, f-strings, format(), or concatenation. If you use SQLAlchemy, prefer the ORM or Core expression language; when executing textual SQL, bind named parameters explicitly. Also validate expected input shape, store passwords with a strong password hashing function rather than raw values, and run the application with a database account that has only the minimum required privileges.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nsql = \"INSERT INTO users (username, password, failures, mfa_enabled, mfa_secret) VALUES (?, ?, ?, ?, ?)\"\nc.execute(sql, (u, p, 0, 0, ''))\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nsqlite3 (Python standard library)\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: SQL Injection](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/SQL_Injection)\n- [OWASP SQL Injection Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/SQL_Injection_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-89: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an SQL Command](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html)\n- [Python sqlite3 documentation](https://docs.python.org/3/library/sqlite3.html)\n- [SQLAlchemy Textual SQL with bound parameters](https://docs.sqlalchemy.org/en/20/core/sqlelement.html#sqlalchemy.sql.expression.text)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-89",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-89"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "73a16a25-e6c0-37c7-9a46-cc7082a66055",
              "name": "Insecure Usage Of Temp File Or Directory",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nInsecure temporary file handling. This code reads a sensitive key from a predictable path under /tmp, which is a shared world-writable directory on many systems. In Python, opening a fixed filename such as /tmp/ca.key allows other local users or processes to pre-create, replace, or symlink that path before it is used.\n\nWhen the file contains private key material, this can lead to unauthorized disclosure, use of attacker-controlled content, or race-condition attacks. The fix is to avoid predictable temporary paths and instead create the file in a secure way with restricted permissions, then pass that trusted path or file handle to the code that needs it.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not use hard-coded filenames in shared temporary directories for sensitive data. Create temporary files with Python's tempfile module so the filename is unpredictable and the file is created atomically. Restrict permissions to the current user, delete the file as soon as it is no longer needed, and prefer keeping private keys in memory or in a dedicated protected directory instead of under /tmp. If another component must consume a path, generate the file securely and pass that path forward rather than reopening a predictable name.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom pathlib import Path\nimport os\nimport tempfile\n\nkey_bytes = get_ca_key_bytes()\n\nfd, key_path = tempfile.mkstemp(prefix=\"ca_\", suffix=\".key\")\ntry:\n    os.fchmod(fd, 0o600)\n    with os.fdopen(fd, \"wb\") as key_file:\n        key_file.write(key_bytes)\n\n    with open(key_path, \"rb\") as key_file:\n        ca_key = key_file.read()\nfinally:\n    try:\n        Path(key_path).unlink()\n    except FileNotFoundError:\n        pass\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\ntempfile\npathlib\nos\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-377: Insecure Temporary File](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html)\n- [CWE-378: Creation of Temporary File With Insecure Permissions](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/378.html)\n- [Python tempfile module](https://docs.python.org/3/library/tempfile.html)\n- [OWASP: Insecure Temporary File](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Insecure_Temporary_File)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-377",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html"
                  },
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-378",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/378.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-377",
                  "CWE-378"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "7827c316-f7c9-3d69-b744-52ea64deaa28",
              "name": "Insecure Usage Of Temp File Or Directory",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nInsecure temporary file handling. This code reads sensitive material from a hard-coded path under /tmp, which is a shared world-writable directory on many systems. In Python, opening a predictable filename in that location can expose the application to symlink attacks, file replacement, race conditions, or unintended disclosure if another user or process can create or modify the file first.\n\nFor a key file such as /tmp/acme.key, the safer approach is to avoid predictable temporary paths entirely and create the file with the tempfile module using restrictive permissions. If the file must persist long enough to be reopened, create it with tempfile.NamedTemporaryFile or tempfile.mkstemp, limit access to the current process, and delete it as soon as it is no longer needed. If the data does not need a filesystem path, keep it in memory instead of writing it to /tmp.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not use fixed filenames in shared temporary directories for sensitive files. Create temporary files with Python's tempfile APIs so the runtime chooses a unique name and the file is created atomically. Restrict permissions to the current user, keep the lifetime of the file as short as possible, and remove it immediately after use. For secrets such as private keys, prefer in-memory handling when the consuming API allows bytes or file-like objects instead of a filesystem path.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nimport os\nimport tempfile\n\nfd, key_path = tempfile.mkstemp(prefix=\"acme_\", suffix=\".key\")\ntry:\n    with os.fdopen(fd, \"wb\") as key_file:\n        key_file.write(key_bytes)\n\n    with open(key_path, \"rb\") as key_file:\n        key_data = key_file.read()\nfinally:\n    if os.path.exists(key_path):\n        os.remove(key_path)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nimport os\nimport tempfile\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-377: Insecure Temporary File](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html)\n- [CWE-378: Creation of Temporary File With Insecure Permissions](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/378.html)\n- [Python tempfile module](https://docs.python.org/3/library/tempfile.html)\n- [OWASP: Insecure Temporary File](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Insecure_Temporary_File)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-377",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html"
                  },
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-378",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/378.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-377",
                  "CWE-378"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "794cfa23-3b60-3d9c-b64d-8e3affa05713",
              "name": "Login Route Lacks Rate Limiting And Throttling",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThis route has insufficient protection against brute-force authentication attempts. The login handler validates a username and password, then optionally validates an MFA code, but it does not visibly limit repeated failures, record failed attempts, or slow repeated submissions.\n\nIn a Flask application, an unthrottled login endpoint lets an attacker automate password guessing and OTP guessing at high speed. Because this handler accepts POSTs directly and returns immediately on invalid credentials or invalid OTP values, an attacker can keep retrying until credentials are found unless the application enforces rate limits, temporary lockouts, or backoff.\n\nProtect this route by applying request throttling to the login endpoint and by tracking authentication failures per account and per client source. After a defined number of failed password or MFA attempts, temporarily block further attempts or require a cooling-off period. Reset the failure counters only after a full successful authentication flow, including MFA when enabled.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nUse layered defenses for authentication endpoints: per-route rate limiting, per-account failure counters, short temporary lockouts, and monitoring for repeated failures. Apply the controls to both password validation and MFA validation so attackers cannot pivot from password guessing to OTP guessing.\n\nStore failure counters in shared server-side storage such as Redis or a database so the protection works across multiple workers and instances. Return a generic authentication error message, avoid revealing whether the username, password, or OTP was wrong, and reset counters only after the entire login process succeeds.\n\nIf this application is deployed behind a proxy or load balancer, configure client IP handling correctly before using IP-based limits. Combine throttling with secure session handling, strong password hashing, MFA, and alerting on suspicious login activity.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom flask import current_app, flash, make_response, redirect, render_template, request\nfrom flask_limiter import Limiter\nfrom flask_limiter.util import get_remote_address\nfrom werkzeug.security import safe_str_cmp\nimport time\n\nlimiter = Limiter(key_func=get_remote_address, default_limits=[])\n\n_login_failures = {}\n_LOCKOUT_SECONDS = 900\n_MAX_FAILURES = 5\n\n\ndef _client_ip():\n    return get_remote_address() or \"unknown\"\n\n\ndef _failure_key(username):\n    return f\"{_client_ip()}:{(username or '').strip().lower()}\"\n\n\ndef _is_locked(username):\n    key = _failure_key(username)\n    entry = _login_failures.get(key)\n    if not entry:\n        return False\n    if entry[\"count\"] < _MAX_FAILURES:\n        return False\n    return time.time() < entry[\"locked_until\"]\n\n\ndef _record_failure(username):\n    key = _failure_key(username)\n    now = time.time()\n    entry = _login_failures.get(key, {\"count\": 0, \"locked_until\": 0})\n    entry[\"count\"] += 1\n    if entry[\"count\"] >= _MAX_FAILURES:\n        entry[\"locked_until\"] = now + _LOCKOUT_SECONDS\n    _login_failures[key] = entry\n\n\ndef _clear_failures(username):\n    _login_failures.pop(_failure_key(username), None)\n\n\n@mod_user.route('/login', methods=['GET', 'POST'])\n@limiter.limit(\"10 per minute; 50 per hour\", methods=[\"POST\"])\ndef do_login():\n    session.pop('username', None)\n\n    if request.method == 'POST':\n        username_input = request.form.get('username', '').strip()\n        password = request.form.get('password', '')\n        otp = request.form.get('otp', '')\n\n        if _is_locked(username_input):\n            flash(\"Too many failed login attempts. Please try again later.\")\n            return render_template('user.login.mfa.html'), 429\n\n        authenticated_username = libuser.login(username_input, password)\n        if not authenticated_username:\n            _record_failure(username_input)\n            flash(\"Invalid user, password, or one-time code\")\n            return render_template('user.login.mfa.html'), 401\n\n        if libmfa.mfa_is_enabled(authenticated_username):\n            if not libmfa.mfa_validate(authenticated_username, otp):\n                _record_failure(authenticated_username)\n                flash(\"Invalid user, password, or one-time code\")\n                return render_template('user.login.mfa.html'), 401\n\n        _clear_failures(authenticated_username)\n        response = make_response(redirect('/'))\n        response = libsession.create(request=request, response=response, username=authenticated_username)\n        return response\n\n    return render_template('user.login.mfa.html')\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nFlask-Limiter\nlimits\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Blocking Brute Force Attacks](https://owasp.org/www-community/controls/Blocking_Brute_Force_Attacks)\n- [OWASP Authentication Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Authentication_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-307: Improper Restriction of Excessive Authentication Attempts](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/307.html)\n- [Flask-Limiter Documentation](https://flask-limiter.readthedocs.io/en/stable/)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-307",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/307.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-307"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "7cdc69ca-991c-3b0f-bb16-422d8d8bbbb0",
              "name": "Hardcoded Fernet Key In Source Code",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nHardcoded encryption key. In Python, embedding a Fernet key directly in source code makes the secret easy to recover from the repository, build artifacts, logs, or deployed bytecode. Anyone who obtains that key can decrypt protected data and forge valid encrypted tokens for this application.\n\nFor the shown sink, the Fernet key is assigned from a string literal and then passed into Fernet(). Replace the inline key with a value loaded at runtime from an environment variable or a dedicated secret manager, validate that it is present, and fail closed if it is missing. Because the key has already been committed in code, rotate it immediately and re-encrypt affected data or tokens as part of the rollout.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not store encryption keys in Python source files, test fixtures, container images, or version control. Load the Fernet key from a runtime secret source such as an environment variable, cloud secret manager, or platform vault, and restrict access to the secret to only the processes that need it. Validate the key during startup and stop the application if it is missing or malformed.\n\nSince the exposed key is no longer trustworthy, generate a new Fernet key, update deployments to use the replacement secret, and revoke the old one. If existing ciphertext or signed tokens depend on the compromised key, plan a migration that decrypts and re-encrypts stored data and expires or reissues tokens created with the old key.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nimport os\nfrom cryptography.fernet import Fernet\n\nkey = os.environ[\"FERNET_KEY\"].encode(\"ascii\")\nfernet = Fernet(key)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\ncryptography\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)\n- [OWASP Secrets Management Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Secrets_Management_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [cryptography.io Fernet Documentation](https://cryptography.io/en/latest/fernet/)\n- [Python os module documentation](https://docs.python.org/3/library/os.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-798"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "81a7fab8-2fda-3dbf-956f-9c5f06bac559",
              "name": "Hardcoded Configuration Detected",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nHardcoded secret in application configuration. In Python, embedding a Flask SECRET_KEY directly in source code exposes sensitive material to anyone who can read the repository, logs, build artifacts, or deployed files. If the key is disclosed, attackers can forge signed session data and weaken the trust boundary of the application.\n\nFor the sink shown here, assigning a literal value to app.config['SECRET_KEY'] should be replaced with loading the secret from the environment or a protected configuration source at runtime. This keeps the key out of version control, allows rotation without code changes, and supports different secrets per environment.\n\nThe application should also fail closed when the secret is missing instead of silently using an insecure default. Use a strong random value generated outside the codebase, store it in deployment secrets management, and rotate it according to operational policy.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nRemove hardcoded secrets from Python source files and load them at runtime from environment variables, a secrets manager, or protected configuration files that are excluded from version control. For Flask, set SECRET_KEY from deployment configuration and ensure production environments provide a strong unpredictable value.\n\nDo not replace the literal with another constant, test value, or fallback embedded in code. Validate that the variable is present during startup, restrict access to the secret in CI/CD and hosting platforms, and rotate the key if it has ever been committed or exposed.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nimport os\n\nsecret_key = os.environ[\"SECRET_KEY\"]\napp.config[\"SECRET_KEY\"] = secret_key\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nos\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Use of Hard-coded Password](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Use_of_hard-coded_password)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)\n- [Flask Configuration Handling](https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/config/#configuration-basics)\n- [Python os.environ documentation](https://docs.python.org/3/library/os.html#os.environ)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-798"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "83a73e6d-d0b3-3b7e-a63b-b13449d67123",
              "name": "Insecure Usage Of Temp File Or Directory",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nInsecure temporary file handling. This code reads sensitive material from a hard-coded path under /tmp, which is a shared world-writable directory on many systems. In Python, opening a predictable filename in that location can expose the application to symlink attacks, file replacement, race conditions, or unintended disclosure if another user or process can create or modify the file first.\n\nFor a key file such as /tmp/acme.key, the safer approach is to avoid predictable temporary paths entirely and create the file with the tempfile module using restrictive permissions. If the file must persist long enough to be reopened, create it with tempfile.NamedTemporaryFile or tempfile.mkstemp, limit access to the current process, and delete it as soon as it is no longer needed. If the data does not need a filesystem path, keep it in memory instead of writing it to /tmp.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not use fixed filenames in shared temporary directories for sensitive files. Create temporary files with Python's tempfile APIs so the runtime chooses a unique name and the file is created atomically. Restrict permissions to the current user, keep the lifetime of the file as short as possible, and remove it immediately after use. For secrets such as private keys, prefer in-memory handling when the consuming API allows bytes or file-like objects instead of a filesystem path.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nimport os\nimport tempfile\n\nfd, key_path = tempfile.mkstemp(prefix=\"acme_\", suffix=\".key\")\ntry:\n    with os.fdopen(fd, \"wb\") as key_file:\n        key_file.write(key_bytes)\n\n    with open(key_path, \"rb\") as key_file:\n        key_data = key_file.read()\nfinally:\n    if os.path.exists(key_path):\n        os.remove(key_path)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nimport os\nimport tempfile\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-377: Insecure Temporary File](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html)\n- [CWE-378: Creation of Temporary File With Insecure Permissions](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/378.html)\n- [Python tempfile module](https://docs.python.org/3/library/tempfile.html)\n- [OWASP: Insecure Temporary File](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Insecure_Temporary_File)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-377",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html"
                  },
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-378",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/378.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
