            {
              "id": "87b7ea15-fc64-3376-a8c5-18f6124c2f23",
              "name": "Missing Function Level Access Control",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nBroken access control in a view function. This endpoint can be invoked without any authentication or authorization checks, so any caller who can reach the route may execute the function and obtain its response.\n\nIn Python web applications, access control must be enforced explicitly on each exposed view or route. The shown function accepts a request object and returns data derived from the client IP address, but it has no guard such as a login requirement or role check. If this route is intended for authenticated users or a restricted audience, the missing check allows unauthorized access.\n\nProtect the view with authentication and, where appropriate, permission checks before processing the request. For a Django-style function view, apply a login decorator and verify the user has the required permission. Keep the geolocation logic, but fail closed on access control so unauthenticated callers are redirected or denied before the function runs.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nRequire authentication on every non-public view and enforce authorization based on the least privilege needed for the action or data being returned. In Django function-based views, use login_required for authentication and permission_required or explicit user permission checks for authorization. Do not rely on URL secrecy, client IP address, or frontend controls as security boundaries. Review routing so this function is only exposed where intended, and define a clear policy for whether the endpoint is public, authenticated, or limited to a specific role. If the endpoint is truly public, document that decision and avoid returning sensitive or user-specific data.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom django.contrib.auth.decorators import login_required, permission_required\n\n@login_required\n@permission_required('app.view_country', raise_exception=True)\ndef getcountry(request):\n    country = 'XX'\n\n    try:\n        geo = reader.country(request.META.get('REMOTE_ADDR', ''))\n        if geo.country and geo.country.iso_code:\n            country = geo.country.iso_code\n    except Exception:\n        pass\n\n    return country\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nDjango\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Broken Access Control](https://owasp.org/www-community/Broken_Access_Control)\n- [OWASP Authorization Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Authorization_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-306: Missing Authentication for Critical Function](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/306.html)\n- [CWE-862: Missing Authorization](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/862.html)\n- [Django authentication in views](https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/stable/topics/auth/default/)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-306",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/306.html"
                  },
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-862",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/862.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-306",
                  "CWE-862"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "8b3b4581-006b-313f-8af7-a1b7bc3a847d",
              "name": "GET Route Performs State-Changing Action",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nImproper use of GET for a state-changing action with missing CSRF protection. In this Flask route, visiting /disable disables MFA for the logged-in user, but the endpoint is exposed as a GET request. GET should be safe and idempotent, so using it for account changes allows an attacker to trigger the action through a link, image, or embedded request.\n\nThe current referer header check is not a reliable defense. Referer may be absent, altered by client privacy settings, or inconsistently enforced, and it should not be the only control protecting sensitive actions. For an operation like disabling multi-factor authentication, require a non-GET method such as POST and enforce a server-validated CSRF token tied to the user session before calling the MFA disable function.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nUse GET only for read-only routes. Any endpoint that changes account settings, authentication state, or stored data should require POST, PUT, PATCH, or DELETE as appropriate, and must reject requests without a valid CSRF token. In Flask applications, enable application-wide CSRF protection and submit sensitive actions through forms or AJAX requests that include the token.\n\nDo not rely on the Referer header as the primary protection for cross-site request forgery. If additional hardening is needed, validate the Origin header when present, use SameSite cookies, and require re-authentication or step-up verification for high-impact actions such as disabling MFA.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom flask import Blueprint, g, redirect, render_template, url_for\nfrom flask_wtf import FlaskForm, CSRFProtect\nfrom wtforms import SubmitField\n\nmod_mfa = Blueprint('mfa', __name__)\ncsrf = CSRFProtect()\n\nclass DisableMFAForm(FlaskForm):\n    submit = SubmitField('Disable MFA')\n\n@mod_mfa.route('/disable', methods=['POST'])\ndef do_mfa_disable():\n    if 'username' not in g.session:\n        return redirect('/user/login')\n\n    form = DisableMFAForm()\n    if not form.validate_on_submit():\n        return redirect(url_for('mfa.mfa_index'))\n\n    libmfa.mfa_disable(g.session['username'])\n    return redirect('/mfa/')\n\n@mod_mfa.route('/', methods=['GET'])\ndef mfa_index():\n    if 'username' not in g.session:\n        return redirect('/user/login')\n\n    form = DisableMFAForm()\n    return render_template('mfa/index.html', form=form)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nFlask-WTF\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Request Forgery](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/csrf)\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Request Forgery Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross-Site_Request_Forgery_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-352: Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html)\n- [Flask-WTF CSRF Protection](https://flask-wtf.readthedocs.io/en/1.2.x/csrf/)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-352",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-352"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "90b2d4ab-dc36-321e-bba5-f5350547cbcf",
              "name": "Hardcoded Configuration Detected",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nHardcoded secret in application configuration. In Python, embedding a Flask SECRET_KEY directly in source code exposes sensitive material to anyone who can read the repository, logs, build artifacts, or deployed files. If the key is disclosed, attackers can forge signed session data and weaken the trust boundary of the application.\n\nFor the sink shown here, assigning a literal value to app.config['SECRET_KEY'] should be replaced with loading the secret from the environment or a protected configuration source at runtime. This keeps the key out of version control, allows rotation without code changes, and supports different secrets per environment.\n\nThe application should also fail closed when the secret is missing instead of silently using an insecure default. Use a strong random value generated outside the codebase, store it in deployment secrets management, and rotate it according to operational policy.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nRemove hardcoded secrets from Python source files and load them at runtime from environment variables, a secrets manager, or protected configuration files that are excluded from version control. For Flask, set SECRET_KEY from deployment configuration and ensure production environments provide a strong unpredictable value.\n\nDo not replace the literal with another constant, test value, or fallback embedded in code. Validate that the variable is present during startup, restrict access to the secret in CI/CD and hosting platforms, and rotate the key if it has ever been committed or exposed.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nimport os\n\nsecret_key = os.environ[\"SECRET_KEY\"]\napp.config[\"SECRET_KEY\"] = secret_key\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nos\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Use of Hard-coded Password](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Use_of_hard-coded_password)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)\n- [Flask Configuration Handling](https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/config/#configuration-basics)\n- [Python os.environ documentation](https://docs.python.org/3/library/os.html#os.environ)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-798"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "9181c227-499c-30af-bf94-5d24533def32",
              "name": "Missing Function Level Access Control",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThis is a broken function-level access control issue. The view function performs a security-sensitive action by creating a session cookie from user-controlled or route-supplied identity data, but it does not enforce authentication or authorization before doing so.\n\nIn Python web applications, a handler like this must not trust a username parameter alone to establish identity. If an unauthenticated caller can reach this function, they may be able to mint a valid session cookie for an arbitrary username, resulting in account impersonation or unauthorized access. The fix is to require an authenticated user at the route level, derive the username from the server-side authenticated principal instead of request input, and deny access when the caller is not authorized to create or refresh that session state.\n\nBecause this sink sets a cookie directly, the remediation should also set secure cookie attributes. Mark the cookie as HttpOnly, Secure, and use an appropriate SameSite policy so the session token is less exposed to client-side script access and cross-site request attacks.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nProtect every state-changing or identity-bearing view with authentication and explicit authorization checks. Do not accept identity from URL parameters, form fields, or other client-controlled input when creating a session or acting on behalf of a user; instead, use the authenticated server-side principal from the framework session or security context.\n\nApply authorization as close to the entry point as possible with framework-native decorators or middleware, then enforce object-level checks inside the function when the route references a specific user. When issuing cookies, always set HttpOnly and Secure, choose a SameSite value appropriate for the application flow, and ensure the encrypted payload contains only trusted server-derived data.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom flask import abort\nfrom flask_login import current_user, login_required\n\n@login_required\ndef create(request, response, username):\n    if current_user.username != username and not getattr(current_user, \"is_admin\", False):\n        abort(403)\n\n    country = getcountry(request)\n    session_value = fernet.encrypt(\n        f\"{current_user.username}|{country}\".encode()\n    ).decode()\n\n    response.set_cookie(\n        \"vulpy_session\",\n        session_value,\n        httponly=True,\n        secure=True,\n        samesite=\"Lax\"\n    )\n\n    return response\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nFlask-Login\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Broken Access Control](https://owasp.org/www-community/Broken_Access_Control)\n- [OWASP Authorization Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Authorization_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-306: Missing Authentication for Critical Function](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/306.html)\n- [CWE-862: Missing Authorization](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/862.html)\n- [Django authentication and authorization](https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/stable/topics/auth/default/)\n- [Flask-Login documentation](https://flask-login.readthedocs.io/)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-306",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/306.html"
                  },
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-862",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/862.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-306",
                  "CWE-862"
                ]
              }
