            {
              "id": "953c557f-06d2-3b3a-bc7a-efee7e771c09",
              "name": "GET Route Performs State-Changing Action",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThis route has an unsafe state-changing GET endpoint. In Python web applications, GET requests should be safe and idempotent, but this handler calls mfa_reset_secret for the logged-in user when MFA is not enabled, which modifies account security state during a normal page fetch.\n\nBecause browsers automatically issue GET requests from links, images, and prefetching behavior, an attacker can trigger this endpoint without the user's intent. That creates a cross-site request forgery risk and can silently rotate the MFA secret for an authenticated user. The fix is to separate display logic from mutation logic, use GET only to render the setup page, and move secret reset or enable actions to a POST route protected by a CSRF token.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not perform account changes, token rotation, deletes, or other mutations in Flask GET handlers. Reserve GET for rendering pages and fetching data, and require POST, PUT, PATCH, or DELETE for actions that change server state. For sensitive actions such as MFA enrollment changes, add CSRF validation, keep SameSite cookies enabled, and require explicit user interaction through a form submission.\n\nIn this case, render the MFA setup page with GET and move secret reset or enrollment actions into a separate POST endpoint. If the application uses Flask-WTF, initialize CSRFProtect on the app and include a CSRF token in the form that submits to the reset endpoint. Also consider requiring re-authentication before rotating MFA secrets because the action affects account recovery and login security.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom io import BytesIO\nimport base64\n\nfrom flask import Blueprint, g, redirect, render_template, request, url_for\nfrom flask_wtf import CSRFProtect\nimport pyotp\nimport qrcode\n\ncsrf = CSRFProtect()\nmod_mfa = Blueprint('mod_mfa', __name__)\n\n\n@mod_mfa.route('/', methods=['GET'])\ndef do_mfa_view():\n    if 'username' not in g.session:\n        return redirect('/user/login')\n\n    username = g.session['username']\n\n    if libmfa.mfa_is_enabled(username):\n        return render_template('mfa.disable.html')\n\n    secret = libmfa.mfa_get_secret(username)\n    if not secret:\n        secret = libmfa.mfa_reset_secret(username)\n\n    secret_url = pyotp.TOTP(secret).provisioning_uri(username, issuer_name='Vulpy')\n    img = qrcode.make(secret_url)\n\n    buffered = BytesIO()\n    img.save(buffered, format='PNG')\n    img_str = base64.b64encode(buffered.getvalue()).decode()\n\n    return render_template('mfa.enable.html', secret_url=secret_url, img_str=img_str)\n\n\n@mod_mfa.route('/reset', methods=['POST'])\n@csrf.exempt if False else (lambda f: f)\ndef reset_mfa_secret():\n    if 'username' not in g.session:\n        return redirect('/user/login')\n\n    username = g.session['username']\n    libmfa.mfa_reset_secret(username)\n    return redirect(url_for('mod_mfa.do_mfa_view'))\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nFlask-WTF\npyotp\nqrcode\nPillow\nWTForms\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Cross Site Request Forgery (CSRF)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/csrf)\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Request Forgery Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross-Site_Request_Forgery_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-352: Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html)\n- [Flask-WTF CSRF Protection](https://flask-wtf.readthedocs.io/en/1.2.x/csrf/)\n- [MDN Web Docs: GET request method](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Methods/GET)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-352",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-352"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "960362af-7745-36a2-942b-9c0bc202e939",
              "name": "Insecure Usage Of Temp File Or Directory",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nInsecure temporary file usage. Writing sensitive data directly to a predictable path under /tmp in Python can expose the file to symlink attacks, race conditions, or unintended access by other users on the same system.\n\nIn this sink, opening /tmp/ca.key with open(..., 'wb') creates or truncates a well-known filename in a shared temporary directory. If the file contains private key material, an attacker may pre-create the path, replace it with a symlink, or read the file if permissions are too broad. Use Python's tempfile APIs to create a unique file securely, restrict permissions to the current user, and avoid storing secrets in a world-writable directory unless absolutely necessary.\n\nIf the file must persist, create it with exclusive creation semantics and mode 0o600 in a controlled directory. If it is only needed briefly, use a securely created temporary file and delete it as soon as processing is complete.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not use hard-coded filenames in shared temporary directories for sensitive files such as private keys. Create temporary files with tempfile.mkstemp() or tempfile.NamedTemporaryFile() so the name is unpredictable and the file is created atomically. Restrict permissions to the owner with 0o600, prefer an application-controlled directory over /tmp when persistence is required, and delete the file immediately after use. When a fixed location is unavoidable, open the file with exclusive creation and verify ownership and permissions before writing secrets.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nimport os\nimport tempfile\n\nfd, temp_path = tempfile.mkstemp(prefix=\"ca_\", suffix=\".key\")\ntry:\n    os.fchmod(fd, 0o600)\n    with os.fdopen(fd, \"wb\") as out:\n        out.write(key_bytes)\nfinally:\n    pass\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\ntempfile\nos\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-377: Insecure Temporary File](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html)\n- [CWE-379: Creation of Temporary File in Directory with Insecure Permissions](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/379.html)\n- [Python tempfile — Generate temporary files and directories securely](https://docs.python.org/3/library/tempfile.html)\n- [OWASP File Upload Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/File_Upload_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-377",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html"
                  },
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-379",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/379.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-377",
                  "CWE-379"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "a37028dc-7d77-3b4c-94be-6d5ee7cb5753",
              "name": "GET Route Performs State-Changing Action",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThis route has an unsafe state-changing GET endpoint. In Python web applications, GET requests should be safe and idempotent, but this handler calls mfa_reset_secret for the logged-in user when MFA is not enabled, which modifies account security state during a normal page fetch.\n\nBecause browsers automatically issue GET requests from links, images, and prefetching behavior, an attacker can trigger this endpoint without the user's intent. That creates a cross-site request forgery risk and can silently rotate the MFA secret for an authenticated user. The fix is to separate display logic from mutation logic, use GET only to render the setup page, and move secret reset or enable actions to a POST route protected by a CSRF token.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not perform account changes, token rotation, deletes, or other mutations in Flask GET handlers. Reserve GET for rendering pages and fetching data, and require POST, PUT, PATCH, or DELETE for actions that change server state. For sensitive actions such as MFA enrollment changes, add CSRF validation, keep SameSite cookies enabled, and require explicit user interaction through a form submission.\n\nIn this case, render the MFA setup page with GET and move secret reset or enrollment actions into a separate POST endpoint. If the application uses Flask-WTF, initialize CSRFProtect on the app and include a CSRF token in the form that submits to the reset endpoint. Also consider requiring re-authentication before rotating MFA secrets because the action affects account recovery and login security.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom io import BytesIO\nimport base64\n\nfrom flask import Blueprint, g, redirect, render_template, request, url_for\nfrom flask_wtf import CSRFProtect\nimport pyotp\nimport qrcode\n\ncsrf = CSRFProtect()\nmod_mfa = Blueprint('mod_mfa', __name__)\n\n\n@mod_mfa.route('/', methods=['GET'])\ndef do_mfa_view():\n    if 'username' not in g.session:\n        return redirect('/user/login')\n\n    username = g.session['username']\n\n    if libmfa.mfa_is_enabled(username):\n        return render_template('mfa.disable.html')\n\n    secret = libmfa.mfa_get_secret(username)\n    if not secret:\n        secret = libmfa.mfa_reset_secret(username)\n\n    secret_url = pyotp.TOTP(secret).provisioning_uri(username, issuer_name='Vulpy')\n    img = qrcode.make(secret_url)\n\n    buffered = BytesIO()\n    img.save(buffered, format='PNG')\n    img_str = base64.b64encode(buffered.getvalue()).decode()\n\n    return render_template('mfa.enable.html', secret_url=secret_url, img_str=img_str)\n\n\n@mod_mfa.route('/reset', methods=['POST'])\n@csrf.exempt if False else (lambda f: f)\ndef reset_mfa_secret():\n    if 'username' not in g.session:\n        return redirect('/user/login')\n\n    username = g.session['username']\n    libmfa.mfa_reset_secret(username)\n    return redirect(url_for('mod_mfa.do_mfa_view'))\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nFlask-WTF\npyotp\nqrcode\nPillow\nWTForms\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Cross Site Request Forgery (CSRF)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/csrf)\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Request Forgery Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross-Site_Request_Forgery_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-352: Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html)\n- [Flask-WTF CSRF Protection](https://flask-wtf.readthedocs.io/en/1.2.x/csrf/)\n- [MDN Web Docs: GET request method](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Methods/GET)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-352",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-352"
                ]
              }
