            {
              "id": "a89e76a8-eb08-33ea-8322-533d074a74af",
              "name": "Missing CSRF Protection In State-Changing Route",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-site request forgery protection is missing on a state-changing Flask route. This login handler accepts POSTed form data and creates an authenticated session, but there is no visible CSRF token validation or request origin verification before processing the submitted credentials and OTP.\n\nIn Flask applications, a POST endpoint that changes authentication state should reject forged cross-site requests. Without CSRF protection, an attacker can cause a victim browser to submit a crafted form to this route, potentially forcing a login flow under attacker-controlled conditions or interfering with session state. Protect this route by enabling framework-level CSRF validation for form posts and by rendering a CSRF token in the HTML form that submits to this endpoint.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nEnable CSRF protection centrally for the Flask application so all unsafe HTTP methods are validated by default, then use FlaskForm or an equivalent mechanism to embed and verify a per-request token on the login form. For this route, read submitted values from the validated form object instead of directly trusting request.form.\n\nAlso harden session handling around authentication. Set a strong SECRET_KEY, mark session cookies Secure, HttpOnly, and SameSite=Lax or Strict as appropriate, and avoid accepting cross-origin POSTs to authentication endpoints. If the application exposes browser-facing state-changing routes outside standard forms, add explicit CSRF checks or Origin/Referer validation as a defense in depth measure.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom flask import Blueprint, flash, make_response, redirect, render_template, request, session\nfrom flask_wtf import FlaskForm, CSRFProtect\nfrom wtforms import PasswordField, StringField, SubmitField\nfrom wtforms.validators import DataRequired\n\ncsrf = CSRFProtect()\n\nclass LoginForm(FlaskForm):\n    username = StringField('Username', validators=[DataRequired()])\n    password = PasswordField('Password', validators=[DataRequired()])\n    otp = StringField('OTP')\n    submit = SubmitField('Log in')\n\nmod_user = Blueprint('mod_user', __name__)\n\n@mod_user.route('/login', methods=['GET', 'POST'])\ndef do_login():\n    session.pop('username', None)\n    form = LoginForm()\n\n    if form.validate_on_submit():\n        username = form.username.data\n        password = form.password.data\n        otp = form.otp.data\n\n        username = libuser.login(username, password)\n\n        if not username:\n            flash('Invalid user or password')\n            return render_template('user.login.mfa.html', form=form), 401\n\n        if libmfa.mfa_is_enabled(username):\n            if not libmfa.mfa_validate(username, otp):\n                flash('Invalid OTP')\n                return render_template('user.login.mfa.html', form=form), 401\n\n        response = make_response(redirect('/'))\n        response = libsession.create(response=response, username=username)\n        return response\n\n    return render_template('user.login.mfa.html', form=form)\n\n# Application setup:\n# app.config['SECRET_KEY'] = 'set-a-strong-secret-key'\n# app.config['WTF_CSRF_TIME_LIMIT'] = 3600\n# csrf.init_app(app)\n\n# In user.login.mfa.html, render the token inside the form:\n# <form method=\"post\" action=\"{{ url_for('mod_user.do_login') }}\">\n#   {{ form.hidden_tag() }}\n#   ...\n# </form>\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nFlask-WTF\nWTForms\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Request Forgery](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/csrf)\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Request Forgery Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross-Site_Request_Forgery_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-352: Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html)\n- [Flask-WTF CSRF Protection](https://flask-wtf.readthedocs.io/en/1.2.x/csrf/)\n- [Flask Security Considerations](https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/web-security/)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-352",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-352"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "aaee5403-4174-3c3b-9e12-6a1eaf31dac3",
              "name": "Login Route Lacks Rate Limiting And Throttling",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThis route has insufficient protection against brute-force authentication attempts. The login handler accepts repeated username, password, and OTP submissions, but it does not visibly enforce request throttling, failure counting, temporary lockout, or backoff before retry.\n\nIn this Flask code, an attacker can automate repeated POST requests to guess passwords or one-time codes at high speed. Because failed password and MFA checks immediately return the login page without slowing or limiting subsequent attempts, the endpoint is exposed to credential stuffing and online guessing attacks.\n\nProtect this flow by applying rate limits to the login route and by tracking failed attempts per account and client origin. After a small number of failures, temporarily block further attempts or require a cooldown period, and reset the failure counter only after a successful authentication. Apply the same controls to both password validation and OTP validation paths so the MFA step cannot be brute-forced independently.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nUse layered controls on authentication endpoints: per-route rate limiting, per-account and per-IP failure counters, and a temporary lockout or exponential backoff after repeated failures. Keep error messages generic enough to avoid account enumeration, and apply the same protections to password and MFA verification steps.\n\nStore counters in shared server-side state such as Redis or a database so limits work across multiple workers and application instances. Expire counters automatically, reset them only after a fully successful login, and log lockouts and bursts of failed attempts for monitoring and alerting.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom flask import Blueprint, flash, make_response, redirect, render_template, request\nfrom flask_limiter import Limiter\nfrom flask_limiter.util import get_remote_address\nfrom time import time\n\nmod_user = Blueprint('mod_user', __name__)\nlimiter = Limiter(key_func=get_remote_address)\n\nFAILED_LOGINS = {}\nMAX_FAILURES = 5\nLOCKOUT_SECONDS = 900\n\n\ndef _client_ip():\n    forwarded_for = request.headers.get('X-Forwarded-For', '')\n    if forwarded_for:\n        return forwarded_for.split(',')[0].strip()\n    return request.remote_addr or 'unknown'\n\n\ndef _failure_key(username):\n    return f\"{username}:{_client_ip()}\"\n\n\ndef _is_locked(username):\n    record = FAILED_LOGINS.get(_failure_key(username))\n    if not record:\n        return False\n    if record['count'] < MAX_FAILURES:\n        return False\n    if time() - record['first_failure'] >= LOCKOUT_SECONDS:\n        FAILED_LOGINS.pop(_failure_key(username), None)\n        return False\n    return True\n\n\ndef _record_failure(username):\n    key = _failure_key(username)\n    now = time()\n    record = FAILED_LOGINS.get(key)\n    if not record or now - record['first_failure'] >= LOCKOUT_SECONDS:\n        FAILED_LOGINS[key] = {'count': 1, 'first_failure': now}\n        return\n    record['count'] += 1\n\n\ndef _reset_failures(username):\n    FAILED_LOGINS.pop(_failure_key(username), None)\n\n\n@mod_user.route('/login', methods=['GET', 'POST'])\n@limiter.limit('10 per minute; 50 per hour', methods=['POST'])\ndef do_login():\n    session.pop('username', None)\n\n    if request.method == 'POST':\n        username_input = (request.form.get('username') or '').strip()\n        password = request.form.get('password') or ''\n        otp = request.form.get('otp') or ''\n\n        if _is_locked(username_input):\n            flash('Too many failed login attempts. Please try again later.')\n            return render_template('user.login.mfa.html'), 429\n\n        authenticated_username = libuser.login(username_input, password)\n\n        if not authenticated_username:\n            _record_failure(username_input)\n            flash('Invalid user or password')\n            return render_template('user.login.mfa.html'), 401\n\n        if libmfa.mfa_is_enabled(authenticated_username):\n            if _is_locked(authenticated_username):\n                flash('Too many failed login attempts. Please try again later.')\n                return render_template('user.login.mfa.html'), 429\n            if not libmfa.mfa_validate(authenticated_username, otp):\n                _record_failure(authenticated_username)\n                flash('Invalid OTP')\n                return render_template('user.login.mfa.html'), 401\n\n        _reset_failures(authenticated_username)\n        response = make_response(redirect('/'))\n        response = libsession.create(response=response, username=authenticated_username)\n        return response\n\n    return render_template('user.login.mfa.html')\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nFlask-Limiter>=3.5.0\nlimits>=3.13.0\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Blocking Brute Force Attacks](https://owasp.org/www-community/controls/Blocking_Brute_Force_Attacks)\n- [OWASP Authentication Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Authentication_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-307: Improper Restriction of Excessive Authentication Attempts](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/307.html)\n- [Flask-Limiter Documentation](https://flask-limiter.readthedocs.io/en/stable/)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-307",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/307.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-307"
                ]
              }
