            {
              "id": "b0656179-b579-3232-91b0-8941f05cd897",
              "name": "Weak Or Broken Hash Function Used",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThis is use of a weak cryptographic hash. In Python, calling hashlib.new(ALGORITHM, ...) with a configurable or legacy algorithm can result in MD5 or SHA-1 being used, which are no longer appropriate for security-sensitive purposes such as integrity protection, signatures, token derivation, or password handling.\n\nFor the shown sink, the fix is to stop selecting the hash algorithm dynamically when it may resolve to a weak primitive, and replace it with an explicit strong algorithm such as SHA-256 or SHA-512. If the value being derived is password-related, a plain hash is still insufficient; use a password-specific KDF such as hashlib.pbkdf2_hmac, scrypt, or Argon2 instead. If the value is meant to protect integrity against tampering, use HMAC with SHA-256 and a secret key rather than a raw hash.\n\nUsing a strong primitive explicitly makes the code deterministic, reviewable, and resistant to downgrade to insecure algorithms. It also prevents accidental reuse of the same hashing pattern in places where collision resistance or preimage resistance is required.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nReplace algorithm agility at this sink with an explicit approved hash such as hashlib.sha256 or hashlib.sha512 when a non-password digest is required. Do not allow untrusted or legacy configuration to choose MD5 or SHA-1. For password storage or password-derived values, use a password KDF such as hashlib.pbkdf2_hmac, hashlib.scrypt, or Argon2 with a per-user random salt and appropriate work factor. For authenticity or tamper detection, use hmac.new(key, data, hashlib.sha256) instead of a plain hash. Document the allowed cryptographic primitives centrally and reject weak algorithms during code review and configuration validation.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nimport hashlib\n\nlastkey = hashlib.sha256(lastkey.encode(\"utf-8\")).hexdigest()\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nhashlib\nhmac\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Password Storage Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Password_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [OWASP Cryptographic Storage Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cryptographic_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-327: Use of a Broken or Risky Cryptographic Algorithm](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/327.html)\n- [Python hashlib documentation](https://docs.python.org/3/library/hashlib.html)\n- [Python hmac documentation](https://docs.python.org/3/library/hmac.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-327",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/327.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-327"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "b3f84613-342e-3f81-965b-e92c9364ce4f",
              "name": "Insecure Usage Of Temp File Or Directory",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nInsecure temporary file handling. Writing directly to a predictable path under /tmp can let another local user interfere with the file by pre-creating it, replacing it with a symlink, or reading it if permissions are too broad.\n\nIn Python, opening /tmp/ca.cert with open(..., 'wb') does not guarantee exclusive creation or safe permissions. If this file contains certificate material or other sensitive data, an attacker on the same system may be able to overwrite it, redirect writes to another path, or access its contents. Use the standard library tempfile APIs to create a unique file securely, restrict permissions, and avoid hard-coded names in shared temporary directories.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nUse tempfile.NamedTemporaryFile, tempfile.mkstemp, or tempfile.TemporaryDirectory instead of hard-coded paths in /tmp. These APIs create unique names securely and reduce race conditions. When the file contains sensitive material, ensure it is readable and writable only by the current process owner, and delete it as soon as it is no longer needed.\n\nIf the file must persist for later use, create it with exclusive creation semantics and store the generated path rather than choosing a predictable filename. Avoid following symlinks, avoid shared writable directories when possible, and prefer keeping certificate data in memory unless a filesystem path is strictly required.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nimport os\nimport tempfile\n\nfd, temp_path = tempfile.mkstemp(prefix=\"ca_\", suffix=\".cert\")\ntry:\n    os.fchmod(fd, 0o600)\n    with os.fdopen(fd, \"wb\") as out:\n        out.write(cert_bytes)\nfinally:\n    pass\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\ntempfile\nos\nio\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-377: Insecure Temporary File](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html)\n- [Python tempfile — Generate temporary files and directories securely](https://docs.python.org/3/library/tempfile.html)\n- [OWASP: Insecure Temporary File](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Insecure_Temporary_File)\n- [CWE-379: Creation of Temporary File in Directory with Insecure Permissions](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/379.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-377",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html"
                  },
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-379",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/379.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-377",
                  "CWE-379"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "b512c722-1030-3cde-aa69-de3b13b00c63",
              "name": "Insecure HTTP Request",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nInsecure transport over HTTP. This request sends data to an http:// endpoint, so the message body and API key header can be exposed to anyone able to observe or modify network traffic between the client and server.\n\nIn Python, requests will protect data in transit when you use an https:// URL and keep certificate verification enabled. For this call, change the endpoint to HTTPS, avoid disabling TLS verification, and ensure the server presents a certificate trusted by the client. If the service is internal, configure it to serve HTTPS rather than posting secrets over cleartext HTTP.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nUse HTTPS for every request that carries credentials, tokens, API keys, session identifiers, or user data. Do not send secrets in cleartext over internal or loopback networks unless the transport is explicitly secured. Keep TLS certificate verification enabled, use certificates issued by a trusted internal or public CA, and fail closed if the endpoint cannot be validated. Where possible, store the base URL in configuration so insecure schemes can be rejected centrally, and add tests or validation that prevent http:// endpoints from being used in production code.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nimport requests\n\nurl = 'https://127.0.1.1:5000/api/post'\nheaders = {\n    'X-APIKEY': api_key,\n}\npayload = {\n    'text': message,\n}\n\nr = requests.post(\n    url,\n    json=payload,\n    headers=headers,\n    timeout=10,\n)\nr.raise_for_status()\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nrequests\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Insecure Transport](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Insecure_Transport)\n- [CWE-319: Cleartext Transmission of Sensitive Information](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/319.html)\n- [Requests: SSL Cert Verification](https://requests.readthedocs.io/en/latest/user/advanced/#ssl-cert-verification)\n- [OWASP Transport Layer Security Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Transport_Layer_Security_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-319",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/319.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "3.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-319"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "b98ba7b4-e8b3-3ced-b6bc-fd96a21470d2",
              "name": "Insecure Usage Of Temp File Or Directory",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nInsecure temporary file usage. This code starts a Python web application with an SSL certificate and private key loaded from predictable paths under /tmp. Files in shared temporary directories are vulnerable to tampering, replacement, symlink attacks, and unintended disclosure if permissions are not tightly controlled.\n\nIn this sink, the private key path is especially sensitive. An attacker on the same system may be able to pre-create, replace, or read files in /tmp depending on filesystem protections and process privileges. The call also enables debug mode, which is not appropriate for production-facing TLS service startup. Store certificate material in a dedicated non-temporary directory with restrictive permissions, and run the server without debug enabled.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not place certificates, private keys, session files, or other security-sensitive assets in world-writable temporary directories such as /tmp. Use a dedicated application-owned directory outside temporary storage, set ownership to the service account, and restrict the private key to owner-only permissions such as 0o600. If temporary files are truly required elsewhere in the application, create them with Python's tempfile module and keep handles open to reduce race conditions.\n\nDisable debug mode for deployed services. Prefer terminating TLS in a production-grade web server or reverse proxy, or at minimum ensure the Python process reads key material from stable, access-controlled paths. Validate file existence, type, and permissions before starting the listener so the application fails closed when TLS assets are misconfigured.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom pathlib import Path\nimport os\n\nfrom flask import Flask\n\napp = Flask(__name__)\n\ncert_path = Path(\"/etc/myapp/tls/server.crt\")\nkey_path = Path(\"/etc/myapp/tls/server.key\")\n\nfor path in (cert_path, key_path):\n    st = path.stat()\n    if not path.is_file():\n        raise RuntimeError(f\"Missing TLS file: {path}\")\n    if path == key_path and (st.st_mode & 0o077):\n        raise RuntimeError(\"TLS private key permissions must be restricted to the owner\")\n\napp.run(\n    debug=False,\n    host=\"127.0.0.1\",\n    ssl_context=(str(cert_path), str(key_path)),\n)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nfrom pathlib import Path\nimport os\nfrom flask import Flask\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-377: Insecure Temporary File](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html)\n- [CWE-378: Creation of Temporary File With Insecure Permissions](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/378.html)\n- [Python tempfile — Generate temporary files and directories securely](https://docs.python.org/3/library/tempfile.html)\n- [Flask Development Server](https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/server/)\n- [Werkzeug Serving Documentation](https://werkzeug.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/serving/)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-377",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html"
                  },
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-378",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/378.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-377",
                  "CWE-378"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "c1440400-b81d-3954-9865-7d78e40816aa",
              "name": "Insecure Usage Of Temp File Or Directory",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nInsecure temporary file usage. This code opens a file from a predictable path under /tmp, which is a shared world-writable directory on many systems. In Python, reading or writing security-relevant material from a fixed filename in /tmp can let another local user pre-create, replace, or link that path to unintended content.\n\nFor the specific sink shown, loading a public key from /tmp/acme.pub is unsafe because the application is trusting file contents from a location that other processes may influence. Use a non-shared application-controlled directory with restrictive permissions for persistent files, or create temporary files with Python's tempfile APIs so the path is unique and securely created before use.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not use hard-coded, predictable filenames in shared temporary directories such as /tmp for trusted input, keys, tokens, or other security-sensitive data. Store persistent files in an application-owned directory with restricted permissions, and validate ownership and permissions before use when appropriate. If the file is truly temporary, create it with tempfile.NamedTemporaryFile, tempfile.mkstemp, or tempfile.TemporaryDirectory so the operating system allocates a unique path securely. Prefer least-privilege file permissions and avoid following attacker-controlled paths, symlinks, or pre-existing files in shared locations.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom pathlib import Path\n\nkey_path = Path(\"/var/lib/acme/keys/acme.pub\")\nkey_path.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)\n\nwith open(key_path, \"rb\") as key_file:\n    public_key = key_file.read()\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\npathlib (Python standard library)\ntempfile (Python standard library)\nos (Python standard library)\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-377: Insecure Temporary File](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html)\n- [CWE-379: Creation of Temporary File in Directory with Insecure Permissions](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/379.html)\n- [Python tempfile — Generate temporary files and directories securely](https://docs.python.org/3/library/tempfile.html)\n- [OWASP: Insecure Temporary File](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Insecure_Temporary_File)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-377",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html"
                  },
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-379",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/379.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-377",
                  "CWE-379"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "c16f1270-f01e-389a-ac1c-8fbe6bbaf464",
              "name": "Missing CSRF Protection In State-Changing Route",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-site request forgery protection is missing on a state-changing Flask endpoint. This POST route accepts form data and performs an authenticated action using the current session, but there is no visible CSRF token validation before calling the write operation.\n\nIn Flask, a user who is already logged in can be tricked into submitting a forged POST request from another site. Because the browser automatically includes the victim's session cookies, the application may create a post as that user without their intent. For this route, protect the form submission with a server-validated CSRF token and reject requests that do not present a valid token.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nEnable CSRF protection globally for the Flask application so all unsafe methods such as POST, PUT, PATCH, and DELETE are checked automatically. If the route is backed by an HTML form, include the CSRF token field in the rendered form and ensure the application uses a strong secret key for token signing. For endpoints that are not browser form submissions, require a dedicated anti-CSRF token or use a design that does not rely on ambient session cookies.\n\nAs an additional defense, configure session cookies with SameSite and Secure attributes and validate Origin or Referer headers for authenticated state-changing requests where appropriate. Do not rely on request.method checks alone, because they do not verify request intent.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom flask import Blueprint, g, redirect, request\nfrom flask_wtf.csrf import CSRFProtect\n\ncsrf = CSRFProtect()\nmod_posts = Blueprint('posts', __name__)\n\n@mod_posts.route('/', methods=['POST'])\ndef do_create():\n    if 'username' not in g.session:\n        return redirect('/user/login')\n\n    username = g.session['username']\n    text = request.form.get('text', '')\n\n    libposts.post(username, text)\n    return redirect('/')\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nFlask-WTF\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/csrf)\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Request Forgery Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross-Site_Request_Forgery_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [Flask-WTF CSRF Protection](https://flask-wtf.readthedocs.io/en/1.2.x/csrf/)\n- [CWE-352: Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-352",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-352"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "c3e435a2-8660-34ac-82d2-e72c5d898b67",
              "name": "Insecure Usage Of Temp File Or Directory",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nInsecure temporary file usage. This code opens a file from a predictable path under /tmp, which is a shared world-writable directory on many systems. In Python, reading or writing security-relevant material from a fixed filename in /tmp can let another local user pre-create, replace, or link that path to unintended content.\n\nFor the specific sink shown, loading a public key from /tmp/acme.pub is unsafe because the application is trusting file contents from a location that other processes may influence. Use a non-shared application-controlled directory with restrictive permissions for persistent files, or create temporary files with Python's tempfile APIs so the path is unique and securely created before use.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not use hard-coded, predictable filenames in shared temporary directories such as /tmp for trusted input, keys, tokens, or other security-sensitive data. Store persistent files in an application-owned directory with restricted permissions, and validate ownership and permissions before use when appropriate. If the file is truly temporary, create it with tempfile.NamedTemporaryFile, tempfile.mkstemp, or tempfile.TemporaryDirectory so the operating system allocates a unique path securely. Prefer least-privilege file permissions and avoid following attacker-controlled paths, symlinks, or pre-existing files in shared locations.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom pathlib import Path\n\nkey_path = Path(\"/var/lib/acme/keys/acme.pub\")\nkey_path.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)\n\nwith open(key_path, \"rb\") as key_file:\n    public_key = key_file.read()\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\npathlib (Python standard library)\ntempfile (Python standard library)\nos (Python standard library)\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-377: Insecure Temporary File](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html)\n- [CWE-379: Creation of Temporary File in Directory with Insecure Permissions](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/379.html)\n- [Python tempfile — Generate temporary files and directories securely](https://docs.python.org/3/library/tempfile.html)\n- [OWASP: Insecure Temporary File](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Insecure_Temporary_File)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-377",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html"
                  },
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-379",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/379.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-377",
                  "CWE-379"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "c8b9cbff-c720-3f8c-9186-cd803860428b",
              "name": "Missing CSRF Protection In State-Changing Route",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-site request forgery protection is missing on a state-changing Flask endpoint. This POST route changes the authenticated user's password based on form data, but there is no visible CSRF token validation or request-origin verification before the update occurs.\n\nIn Flask applications, relying on a session cookie alone is not sufficient for sensitive actions such as password changes, because the browser will automatically attach that cookie to cross-site requests. An attacker can exploit this by causing a logged-in user to submit a forged POST request that changes account state without the user's intent.\n\nProtect this route by enabling framework-level CSRF validation and requiring a per-request token in the password-change form. For this sink, the most direct fix is to initialize Flask-WTF CSRF protection for the application and validate the token in the POST handler before reading or acting on submitted form fields.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nEnable CSRF protection globally for the Flask application instead of trying to secure individual password-changing routes ad hoc. Use a server-side secret, include a hidden CSRF token in every HTML form that performs a state-changing action, and reject requests with missing or invalid tokens before processing form data.\n\nFor sensitive endpoints such as password changes, keep the route limited to POST, validate the CSRF token through Flask-WTF or equivalent middleware, and ensure cookies used for authentication are configured with Secure, HttpOnly, and an appropriate SameSite policy. If this endpoint is intended for browser form submissions, token-based CSRF validation is the primary control; Origin or Referer checks can be added as a defense in depth but should not replace the token.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom flask import Blueprint, flash, g, redirect, render_template, request\nfrom flask_wtf import FlaskForm, CSRFProtect\nfrom wtforms import PasswordField\nfrom wtforms.validators import DataRequired, EqualTo\n\ncsrf = CSRFProtect()\n\nclass ChangePasswordForm(FlaskForm):\n    current_password = PasswordField('Current password', validators=[DataRequired()])\n    new_password = PasswordField('New password', validators=[DataRequired()])\n    new_password_again = PasswordField(\n        'Repeat new password',\n        validators=[DataRequired(), EqualTo('new_password')]\n    )\n\nmod_user = Blueprint('mod_user', __name__)\n\n\ndef init_app(app):\n    app.config['SECRET_KEY'] = app.config['SECRET_KEY']\n    app.config.setdefault('WTF_CSRF_TIME_LIMIT', 3600)\n    csrf.init_app(app)\n\n\n@mod_user.route('/chpasswd', methods=['GET', 'POST'])\ndef do_chpasswd_post():\n    if 'username' not in g.session:\n        return redirect('/')\n\n    form = ChangePasswordForm()\n\n    if request.method == 'POST':\n        if not form.validate_on_submit():\n            flash('Invalid or missing form token')\n            return render_template('user.chpasswd.html', form=form), 400\n\n        current_password = form.current_password.data\n        new_password = form.new_password.data\n        new_password_again = form.new_password_again.data\n\n        if not libuser.login(g.session['username'], current_password):\n            flash('Invalid current password')\n            return render_template('user.chpasswd.html', form=form)\n\n        if new_password != new_password_again:\n            flash(\"The passwords don't match\")\n            return render_template('user.chpasswd.html', form=form)\n\n        if not libuser.is_password_allowed(new_password):\n            flash(\"The password don't comply our requirements, please, choose another one.\")\n            return render_template('user.chpasswd.html', form=form)\n\n        libuser.password_set(g.session['username'], new_password)\n        flash('Password changed')\n        return redirect('/')\n\n    return render_template('user.chpasswd.html', form=form)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nFlask-WTF\nWTForms\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Request Forgery](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/csrf)\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Request Forgery Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross-Site_Request_Forgery_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-352: Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html)\n- [Flask-WTF CSRF Protection](https://flask-wtf.readthedocs.io/en/1.2.x/csrf/)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-352",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-352"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "d33c8327-ef1c-3df4-87fe-463068e35e85",
              "name": "Sql Injection Via String Formatting",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nSQL injection in Python database code. The statement is assembled with Python string interpolation and then sent to execute(), which mixes SQL syntax with untrusted values. If the username or password contains quotes or crafted SQL fragments, the database may interpret that input as part of the command instead of as data.\n\nIn this sink, the INSERT statement should use DB-API parameters and pass the values separately to execute(). That lets the driver bind the user and password as data, preserves correct quoting and type handling, and prevents attacker-controlled input from changing the SQL structure. Keep the SQL text constant and supply dynamic values only through placeholders.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not build SQL with %, .format(), f-strings, or string concatenation when any part comes from variables. Use the parameter style required by the Python driver and pass parameters as a separate tuple or sequence to execute() or executemany(). Validate input for business rules such as length and allowed characters, but do not rely on validation as a substitute for parameter binding. If table names, column names, or sort directions must vary, choose them from a fixed allowlist rather than accepting raw input.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nsql = \"INSERT INTO users (user, password, failures) VALUES (?, ?, ?)\"\nc.execute(sql, (u, p, 0))\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nsqlite3\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: SQL Injection](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/SQL_Injection)\n- [OWASP SQL Injection Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/SQL_Injection_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-89: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an SQL Command](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html)\n- [Python sqlite3 documentation](https://docs.python.org/3/library/sqlite3.html)\n- [PEP 249: Python Database API Specification v2.0](https://peps.python.org/pep-0249/)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-89",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-89"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "d53787a8-fd0f-373b-9516-bb622994737f",
              "name": "Missing Function Level Access Control",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nBroken access control in a Python view or request handler can allow callers to reach protected functionality without a reliable authentication and authorization check. The shown authentication helper trusts a user-supplied X-APIKEY header and treats the presence of a matching file name under /tmp as proof of identity, which is not a safe access-control mechanism.\n\nThis implementation is also vulnerable because it builds a filesystem glob pattern directly from untrusted input. An attacker can supply wildcard characters in the header and influence which files match, potentially bypassing identity checks. Access control should be enforced before the protected function runs, using a server-side credential lookup and an explicit authorization decision tied to the requested action.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nEnforce authentication and authorization at the entry point of every protected view, not only inside business logic. Use a decorator, middleware, or framework permission class so requests are rejected before sensitive code executes.\n\nDo not derive identity from filenames or any filesystem pattern built from client input. Validate API key format strictly, compare keys with constant-time comparison, and resolve the principal from a trusted server-side store such as a database, secret manager, or framework authentication backend. If file-backed storage is unavoidable, treat the key as opaque data, never interpolate it into glob patterns, and check authorization separately from authentication.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom pathlib import Path\nimport hmac\nimport re\nfrom secrets import compare_digest\n\nAPIKEY_RE = re.compile(r\"^[A-Za-z0-9_-]{32,64}$\")\nKEY_STORE = {\n    \"0123456789abcdef0123456789abcdef\": \"service-account\"\n}\n\ndef authenticate(request):\n    key = request.headers.get(\"X-APIKEY\")\n    if not key or not APIKEY_RE.fullmatch(key):\n        return None\n\n    for stored_key, principal in KEY_STORE.items():\n        if compare_digest(key, stored_key):\n            return principal\n    return None\n\ndef require_authenticated(view_func):\n    def wrapper(request, *args, **kwargs):\n        principal = authenticate(request)\n        if principal is None:\n            return {\"status\": 401, \"detail\": \"authentication required\"}\n        request.principal = principal\n        return view_func(request, *args, **kwargs)\n    return wrapper\n\n@require_authenticated\ndef protected_view(request):\n    return {\"status\": 200, \"user\": request.principal}\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\npathlib\nre\nsecrets\nhmac\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Top 10: Broken Access Control](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A5_2017-Broken_Access_Control)\n- [OWASP Authorization Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Authorization_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-306: Missing Authentication for Critical Function](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/306.html)\n- [CWE-285: Improper Authorization](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/285.html)\n- [Python pathlib documentation](https://docs.python.org/3/library/pathlib.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-306",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/306.html"
                  },
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-285",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/285.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-306",
                  "CWE-285"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "d8af9b34-61fb-3d1d-b42e-f6d41de03587",
              "name": "Insecure Usage Of Temp File Or Directory",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nInsecure temporary file handling. Opening a fixed path under /tmp directly in Python can expose the application to symlink attacks, race conditions, and unintended disclosure or overwrite of sensitive data.\n\nIn this sink, writing certificate data to /tmp/acme.cert is risky because /tmp is typically shared and world-writable on multi-user systems. Another local user or process can pre-create the path, replace it with a symbolic link, or read the file if permissions are too broad. For certificate material, this can lead to credential exposure or corruption.\n\nUse Python's tempfile APIs to create a unique file securely, restrict permissions to the current process, and avoid predictable names. If the file must persist, create it with mkstemp or NamedTemporaryFile in a controlled directory and set mode 0o600 before writing the content.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not write sensitive data to a hard-coded filename in /tmp or any shared temporary directory. Generate temporary files with the standard library so the name is unpredictable and the creation is atomic. For files that contain certificates, keys, tokens, or other sensitive material, ensure permissions are restricted to the current user, prefer a private application-controlled directory when possible, and delete the file as soon as it is no longer needed. Avoid following attacker-controlled paths or symlinks, and never rely on checking for existence before creating the file.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nimport os\nimport tempfile\n\nfd, cert_path = tempfile.mkstemp(prefix=\"acme-\", suffix=\".cert\")\ntry:\n    os.fchmod(fd, 0o600)\n    with os.fdopen(fd, \"wb\") as out:\n        out.write(cert_bytes)\nfinally:\n    pass\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nimport os\nimport tempfile\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-377: Insecure Temporary File](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html)\n- [CWE-379: Creation of Temporary File in Directory with Insecure Permissions](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/379.html)\n- [Python tempfile — Generate temporary files and directories securely](https://docs.python.org/3/library/tempfile.html)\n- [OWASP: Insecure Temporary File](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Insecure_Temporary_File)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-377",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html"
                  },
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-379",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/379.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-377",
                  "CWE-379"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "dcd72da4-3bf6-3c47-9d8b-f374faf099a3",
              "name": "Hardcoded JWT Secret Or Private Key Used",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nHardcoded JWT signing secret is an insufficiently protected credentials issue. In Python, embedding the secret used by jwt.encode directly in code makes it easy to leak through source control, build artifacts, logs, or error reports. Once exposed, an attacker can forge valid tokens and impersonate users.\n\nFor the shown sink, the signing key passed as the secret argument for HS256 must be loaded from a protected configuration source instead of being embedded in the application. Read the secret from an environment variable or a dedicated secret manager, validate that it is present at startup, and fail closed if it is missing. Rotate the secret if a hardcoded value has ever been committed.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not store JWT secrets, API keys, passwords, or private keys in Python source files, tests, notebooks, or default settings modules. Load secrets from environment variables for simple deployments, or use a managed secret store such as AWS Secrets Manager, Azure Key Vault, Google Secret Manager, or HashiCorp Vault. Restrict access to the secret, avoid printing it, and rotate it immediately if it was ever hardcoded or committed.\n\nPrefer short token lifetimes and keep signing configuration centralized so all token issuance uses the same protected secret-loading path. If asymmetric signing fits the application, consider RS256 or ES256 so private keys remain only on the issuer and verifiers use a public key.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nimport os\nfrom datetime import datetime, timedelta, timezone\n\nimport jwt\n\nJWT_SECRET = os.environ[\"JWT_SECRET\"]\n\nif len(JWT_SECRET) < 32:\n    raise RuntimeError(\"JWT_SECRET must be at least 32 characters long\")\n\nnow = datetime.now(timezone.utc)\nnot_after = timedelta(minutes=15)\n\npayload = {\n    \"username\": username,\n    \"nbf\": now,\n    \"exp\": now + not_after,\n}\n\ntoken = jwt.encode(payload, JWT_SECRET, algorithm=\"HS256\")\nif isinstance(token, bytes):\n    token = token.decode(\"utf-8\")\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nPyJWT\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-522: Insufficiently Protected Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/522.html)\n- [OWASP Secrets Management Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Secrets_Management_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [PyJWT Usage Examples](https://pyjwt.readthedocs.io/en/stable/usage.html)\n- [The Twelve-Factor App: Store config in the environment](https://12factor.net/config)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-522",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/522.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-522"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "e28b869e-bbb8-3e20-938b-ec20c56f2edb",
              "name": "Flask App Running In Debug Mode",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThis is an enabled debug mode vulnerability. In Python Flask applications, starting the development server with debug mode turned on exposes interactive debugging features that are not safe for deployed environments.\n\nIn this sink, the application is launched with app.run(debug=True, host='127.0.1.1', ssl_context=('/tmp/acme.cert', '/tmp/acme.key')). Even when TLS is configured and the bind address is loopback-like, debug mode still enables the Werkzeug debugger and verbose error handling. If the service is ever exposed through port forwarding, a reverse proxy, container networking, or misconfiguration, an attacker may gain access to sensitive stack traces or interactive code execution. The fix is to disable debug mode and run the application with production-safe settings.\n\nFor Flask, keep debug disabled in runtime code, do not hardcode development flags in the application entry point, and rely on environment-specific configuration. Use a production WSGI server for deployed workloads and keep certificate handling and network exposure separate from development-only debugging behavior.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDisable Flask debug mode in all deployed environments and remove hardcoded debug=True from the application startup path. Keep development-only behavior behind environment-based configuration that defaults to secure values. Do not rely on loopback binding or TLS alone to make the debugger safe, because container publishing, SSH tunnels, reverse proxies, and network policy mistakes can still expose the service. For production, serve the Flask app with a WSGI server such as gunicorn or uWSGI, keep Werkzeug's debugger disabled, and restrict operational error details to server-side logs instead of user-facing responses.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom flask import Flask\n\napp = Flask(__name__)\n\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    app.run(debug=False, host=\"127.0.1.1\", ssl_context=(\"/tmp/acme.cert\", \"/tmp/acme.key\"))\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nflask\ngunicorn\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [Flask Documentation: Debugging Application Errors](https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/debugging/)\n- [Werkzeug Documentation: Debugger](https://werkzeug.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/debug/)\n- [OWASP Top 10](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/)\n- [CWE-489: Active Debug Code](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/489.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-489",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/489.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-489"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "e4ff3837-2451-3bba-bd07-2c6950436dae",
              "name": "Insecure HTTP Request",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nInsecure transport over HTTP. This request uses plain HTTP, so data sent to and received from the endpoint is not encrypted in transit. In Python, a call such as requests.get(...) over http:// allows network observers or intermediaries to read or modify traffic, which can expose identifiers, session data, API responses, and other sensitive information.\n\nFor this sink, the request is built with requests.get('http://127.0.1.1:5000/api/post/{}'.format(username)), which should be changed to HTTPS so the connection is protected with TLS. Keep certificate verification enabled and avoid disabling warnings or passing verify=False, because doing so defeats transport security even when using https://.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nUse https:// for all application and API traffic, including internal service calls, and ensure the server is configured with a valid TLS certificate. In Python requests, rely on the default certificate verification behavior and do not set verify=False. When path segments include user-controlled data, URL-encode them before composing the request URL. Prefer explicit timeouts and centralized configuration for trusted base URLs so insecure schemes are not introduced accidentally.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom urllib.parse import quote\nimport requests\n\nusername_safe = quote(username, safe='')\nr = requests.get(\n    f'https://127.0.1.1:5000/api/post/{username_safe}',\n    timeout=10\n)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nrequests\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Insecure Transport](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Insecure_Transport)\n- [CWE-319: Cleartext Transmission of Sensitive Information](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/319.html)\n- [Requests: SSL Cert Verification](https://requests.readthedocs.io/en/latest/user/advanced/#ssl-cert-verification)\n- [Python ssl module](https://docs.python.org/3/library/ssl.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-319",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/319.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "3.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-319"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "e508a6cb-937f-3774-88fb-3c12971cfc03",
              "name": "Hardcoded Configuration Detected",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nHardcoded secret in application configuration. In Python web applications, embedding a Flask SECRET_KEY directly in source code exposes a sensitive value to anyone who can read the repository, build artifacts, logs, or error traces.\n\nIn the shown sink, assigning a literal value to app.config['SECRET_KEY'] makes session signing dependent on a secret that is difficult to rotate and likely to be reused across environments. If this key is disclosed, attackers may be able to forge session data or tamper with other security features that rely on the application's secret configuration.\n\nLoad the secret from an environment variable or a protected configuration source instead of storing it in code. Fail closed when the value is missing so the application does not start with an unsafe default, and rotate any previously committed secret value.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nStore application secrets outside the codebase in environment variables, a secrets manager, or deployment-specific protected configuration. Do not commit real secret values to version control, and do not replace them with predictable defaults. For Flask, use a strong random SECRET_KEY generated with a cryptographically secure source, set it per environment, and rotate it if it was ever exposed. Restrict access to the secret in deployment systems, and ensure local development uses separate non-production secret material loaded from a secure developer configuration path.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nimport os\n\nsecret_key = os.environ.get(\"FLASK_SECRET_KEY\")\nif not secret_key:\n    raise RuntimeError(\"FLASK_SECRET_KEY environment variable is required\")\n\napp.config[\"SECRET_KEY\"] = secret_key\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nimport os\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Use of hard-coded password](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Use_of_hard-coded_password)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)\n- [Flask Documentation: SECRET_KEY](https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/config/#secret-key)\n- [Python Documentation: secrets — Generate secure random numbers](https://docs.python.org/3/library/secrets.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-798"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "e54127ae-9b84-32eb-a017-f5d07467703d",
              "name": "Flask App Running In Debug Mode",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThis issue is an enabled debug mode in a production web application. In Flask, setting debug=True starts the interactive Werkzeug debugger, which can expose detailed stack traces, application state, environment data, and in unsafe deployments can enable arbitrary code execution.\n\nIn this sink, the application is started with app.run(debug=True, host='127.0.1.1', port=5001, extra_files='csp.txt'). The fix is to disable debug mode in runtime code and rely on a safe configuration value from the environment when debugging is intentionally needed during local development only. Production deployments should run with debug disabled and use a production WSGI server instead of the built-in development server.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not hardcode debug=True in Flask startup code. Keep debugging disabled by default and enable it only in local development through an environment variable or framework configuration that is not used in production. Do not expose the Flask development server to untrusted users, and deploy the application behind a production-grade WSGI server such as gunicorn or uWSGI. Review deployment settings to ensure stack traces, interactive consoles, and development reload features are not reachable in runtime environments that handle real traffic.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nimport os\nfrom flask import Flask\n\napp = Flask(__name__)\n\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    debug_enabled = os.getenv(\"FLASK_DEBUG\", \"0\") == \"1\"\n    app.run(debug=debug_enabled, host=\"127.0.1.1\", port=5001, extra_files=[\"csp.txt\"])\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nFlask\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [Flask Documentation: Debugging Application Errors](https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/debugging/)\n- [Werkzeug Documentation: Debugger](https://werkzeug.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/debug/)\n- [CWE-489: Active Debug Code](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/489.html)\n- [OWASP Top 10](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-489",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/489.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-489"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "e54de0bd-3865-3a5f-a952-7e8a3be09677",
              "name": "Insecure Usage Of Temp File Or Directory",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nInsecure temporary file usage. Opening a fixed path under /tmp in Python can expose the code to race conditions, symlink attacks, and unintended data disclosure because /tmp is typically shared and writable by other users on the system.\n\nIn this sink, reading /tmp/acme.csr assumes the file at that path is the expected certificate request. An attacker who can write to /tmp can replace that path with a different file or a symlink before it is opened, causing the application to read attacker-controlled content or sensitive data from another location. The fix is to avoid predictable temporary filenames and use Python's tempfile APIs to create and access temporary files securely with restrictive permissions.\n\nIf the CSR must persist long enough to be reopened, create it with tempfile.NamedTemporaryFile or mkstemp and keep track of the returned path or file descriptor instead of reconstructing a hard-coded name in /tmp. If the file already exists for workflow reasons, place it in a directory with restricted permissions that is not shared across users.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not use predictable names such as /tmp/acme.csr for temporary data. Create temporary files with tempfile so the operating system allocates a unique name and restrictive permissions. Prefer keeping and reusing the file descriptor returned at creation time instead of reopening by path. When a path must be reused, store the file in an application-controlled directory with mode 0700 or equivalent, validate ownership and permissions, and remove it as soon as it is no longer needed.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nimport os\nimport tempfile\n\nfd, csr_path = tempfile.mkstemp(suffix=\".csr\")\ntry:\n    with os.fdopen(fd, \"wb\") as csr_file:\n        csr_file.write(csr_bytes)\n\n    with open(csr_path, \"rb\") as csr_file:\n        csr_data = csr_file.read()\nfinally:\n    try:\n        os.remove(csr_path)\n    except FileNotFoundError:\n        pass\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\ntempfile\nos\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-377: Insecure Temporary File](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html)\n- [Python tempfile — Generate temporary files and directories securely](https://docs.python.org/3/library/tempfile.html)\n- [OWASP: Insecure Temporary File](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Insecure_Temporary_File)\n- [CWE-379: Creation of Temporary File in Directory with Insecure Permissions](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/379.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-377",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html"
                  },
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-379",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/379.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-377",
                  "CWE-379"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "ea965aa1-f1e1-3989-93f9-be7439e48dd0",
              "name": "Missing Function Level Access Control",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nMissing function-level access control. In Python web applications, validating a bearer token in a helper function is not sufficient unless each protected view explicitly enforces both authentication and authorization before executing sensitive logic.\n\nThe shown function only extracts a username from a JWT and returns it to the caller. If a view calls this helper inconsistently, ignores a None result, or fails to verify the caller's roles or permissions, unauthenticated or underprivileged users can reach protected functionality. The fix is to make access checks mandatory at the view boundary and to reject requests with clear HTTP errors when the token is missing, invalid, or the user lacks the required permission.\n\nFor this sink, replace the permissive helper with a decorator that validates the Authorization header, decodes the JWT with strict algorithm checking, stores the authenticated principal on the request object, and enforces a required role before the wrapped function runs. This makes the security check uniform and harder to bypass.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nApply authentication and authorization at the entry point of every protected route, not only in shared helper functions. Fail closed: return 401 when authentication is missing or invalid, and 403 when the authenticated user lacks the required role or permission. Do not rely on a returned username alone as proof that access is allowed.\n\nUse a centralized decorator or middleware so the check is consistently enforced across all sensitive endpoints. Validate JWTs with an explicit algorithm allowlist, require expected claims, and attach the authenticated principal to request-scoped state instead of passing raw tokens or usernames through the codebase. Avoid broad exception handlers and debug prints for security decisions; catch token-validation exceptions explicitly and emit controlled error responses.\n\nIf the application has different privilege levels, map endpoints to roles or permissions and verify them on every request. Also ensure the signing secret is stored securely in environment or secret management, use short token lifetimes, and rotate keys as part of operational security.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom functools import wraps\nimport jwt\nfrom jwt import InvalidTokenError\nfrom flask import request, g, jsonify\n\nSECRET_KEY = \"change-this-secret\"\nALGORITHM = \"HS256\"\n\ndef require_auth(required_role=None):\n    def decorator(view_func):\n        @wraps(view_func)\n        def wrapped(*args, **kwargs):\n            auth_header = request.headers.get(\"Authorization\", \"\")\n            parts = auth_header.split()\n\n            if len(parts) != 2 or parts[0].lower() != \"bearer\":\n                return jsonify({\"error\": \"Authentication required\"}), 401\n\n            token = parts[1]\n\n            try:\n                claims = jwt.decode(token, SECRET_KEY, algorithms=[ALGORITHM])\n            except InvalidTokenError:\n                return jsonify({\"error\": \"Invalid token\"}), 401\n\n            username = claims.get(\"username\")\n            roles = claims.get(\"roles\", [])\n\n            if not username:\n                return jsonify({\"error\": \"Invalid token claims\"}), 401\n\n            if required_role and required_role not in roles:\n                return jsonify({\"error\": \"Forbidden\"}), 403\n\n            g.current_user = {\n                \"username\": username,\n                \"roles\": roles,\n                \"claims\": claims,\n            }\n\n            return view_func(*args, **kwargs)\n        return wrapped\n    return decorator\n\n@require_auth(required_role=\"admin\")\ndef protected_view():\n    return jsonify({\"message\": f\"Hello {g.current_user['username']}\"}), 200\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nPyJWT\nFlask\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Broken Access Control](https://owasp.org/www-community/Broken_Access_Control)\n- [OWASP Authorization Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Authorization_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [OWASP Authentication Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Authentication_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-285: Improper Authorization](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/285.html)\n- [PyJWT Usage Examples](https://pyjwt.readthedocs.io/en/stable/usage.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-285",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/285.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-285"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "ea97ea0d-3d9d-310e-bd68-dac366f7cebf",
              "name": "Insecure Deserialization Of Client Cookie Data",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nClient-controlled session state without integrity protection. The code decodes a cookie and immediately deserializes it with json.loads, which treats attacker-supplied data as trusted application state.\n\nIn Python, base64 and JSON provide encoding and parsing, not authenticity. A user can modify the cookie contents, re-encode them, and send forged values such as elevated roles, altered user identifiers, or flags that change authorization behavior. Because the sink shown loads the data directly, any downstream logic that trusts session becomes vulnerable to tampering.\n\nFix this by either storing session state on the server and keeping only an opaque session identifier in the cookie, or by signing the serialized cookie value and verifying the signature before loading it. If verification fails, reject the cookie and create a new unauthenticated session instead of processing attacker-controlled state.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not trust decoded cookie content as authoritative state. Base64 is only a transport encoding and JSON is only a serialization format; neither prevents tampering. Keep sensitive session data on the server when possible, and send only a random session ID in the cookie.\n\nIf stateless cookies are required, protect them with a keyed integrity mechanism such as an HMAC or a well-vetted signed serializer, and verify the signature before deserialization. Reject invalid, expired, or malformed cookies, rotate signing keys safely, and mark cookies Secure, HttpOnly, and SameSite to reduce exposure through other attack paths.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom itsdangerous import BadSignature, URLSafeSerializer\n\nserializer = URLSafeSerializer(\"replace-with-strong-secret-key\", salt=\"session-cookie\")\n\n\ndef load_session_from_cookie(cookie_value: str) -> dict:\n    if not cookie_value:\n        return {}\n\n    try:\n        data = serializer.loads(cookie_value)\n    except BadSignature:\n        return {}\n\n    if not isinstance(data, dict):\n        return {}\n\n    return data\n\n\ndef dump_session_to_cookie(session: dict) -> str:\n    return serializer.dumps(session)\n\n\nsession = load_session_from_cookie(cookie)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nitsdangerous\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Insecure Deserialization](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Insecure_Deserialization)\n- [OWASP Session Management Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Session_Management_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-345: Insufficient Verification of Data Authenticity](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/345.html)\n- [Python hmac module](https://docs.python.org/3/library/hmac.html)\n- [itsdangerous Documentation](https://itsdangerous.palletsprojects.com/)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-345",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/345.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-345"
                ]
              }
            }
          ],
          "language": "en-US",
          "contents": [
            "localizedData",
            "nonLocalizedData"
          ],
          "isComprehensive": false
        }
      },
